<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Exchange Rate Against Ruble Rising in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The exchange rate is ranging
between 8.8 and 9.57 rubles for one U.S. dollar on Wednesday
despite the invalidation of dollar trading at the Moscow Interbank
Currency Exchange (MICEX), the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Some exchange offices change the rate five times on Wednesday
morning, saying demand exceeds supply greatly.
</P>
<P>
However, the growing dollar selling rate has not changed
Russia's financial situation since most of the offices have no
U.S. currency in cash.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, quotations of gas giant Gazprom shares drop
by 14 percent at noon time at the Moscow Stock Exchange with one
unit fetching 1.05 rubles.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow Stock Exchange index drops by 9.17 percent as
compared with that of Tuesday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There was a sharp increase in interest in Gazprom share in the
previous two days as Viktor Chernomyrdin, president of Gazprom,
was appointed acting prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In the first two days of the week prices of Gazprom shares
rose from 0.8 to 1.22 rubles, which was linked by the business
circles to the shareholders' speculation for a rise.
</P>
<P>
Quotations of Gazprom shares began falling as the dollar rate
soared and considerable part of the ruble supply was transferred
from the Moscow Stock Exchange to foreign currency auctions at the
MICEX.
</P>
<P>
Andrei Cherepanov, chief of the foreign operations department
of the Russian Central Bank, said the Central Bank has decided not to
spend large sums of currency reserves and not to prohibit
commercial banks to trade in foreign currencies among themselves.
</P>
<P>
MICEX Wednesday for the first time cancels its trading
session on the dollar, Cherepanov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
