<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair on Wednesday
defended his newly announced measures against terrorism in
Northern Ireland and insisted the peace process must be pushed
forward.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that we carry forward the process of political
development and dialogue, too," Blair said in Northern Irish
capital Belfast.(UK-Blair-Terrorism)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA -- The Zimbabwean military has said the Tutsi-led rebel
forces fighting to topple President Laurent Kabila of the
Democratic Republic Congo (DRC) were stopped by a cordon of
Zimbabwean troops about 80 kilometers west of Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
In its first official military briefing since Angolan,
Zimbabwean and some Namibian troops were reportedly deployed last
Thursday to the DRC to help Kabila, the Zimbabwean army also said
Tuesday night that Ugandan and Rwandan troops were among large
numbers of the rebels captured in the west of the country,
according to a report dispatched by Deutsche Presse-Agentur DPA
Wednesday.(Zambia-DRC-rebels stopped)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin issued a decree of
restructuring the repayment on the treasury bills (T-bills) and
federal loan bonds with fixed income (OFZ) in an attempt to
stabilize the country's financial system.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency Wednesday quoted the Kremlin press
service as saying that Yeltsin instructed Acting Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin to draft a procedure for restructuring matured
treasury bills, including the state short-term couponless bonds
(GKO) and the federal bonds with a fixed and variable coupon
income (OFZ).(Russia-Economy-Yeltsin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- An Iranian single-engine plane crashed Wednesday
morning in northern Iran, killing head of the Iran's Civil
Aviation Organization Ali Shahcheraghi.
</P>
<P>
The plane crashed at 0845 hours local time (0415 GMT) in Bijeh
near Rasht, Gilan province, due to heavy fog, the official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Shahcheraghi was killed together with two pilots of the plane
in the crash, it said.(Iran-Plane Crash-Deaths)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's economic growth declined to minus five
percent in the first half of this year based on measured gross
domestic product (GDP), the lowest growth rate since the end of
the Korean War in 1953, the Bank of Korea said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the bank Chon Chol-whan told a press conference
that South Korea will continue a negative economic growth in the
second half of this year due to reduction in domestic consumption
and sluggish exports.(SKorea-Economy-Decline)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- A tiny, radical group calling itself Muslims
Against Global Oppression has claimed responsibility for Cape Town
bombing in a telephone call to a Cape Town radio station.
</P>
<P>
The caller said that the blast was in retaliation for United
States attacks on suspected terrorists' bases in Sudan and
Afghanistan. He declared that the "Jihad", or "holy war", had
begun.(Africa-Muslim Group) 
</P>
