<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders for Durable Goods Pick Up in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to surging demand for
semiconductors and other electronical equipments, the U.S. orders
for durable goods shot up in July, the Commerce Department
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Orders to U.S. factories for durable goods rose 2.4 percent to
a seasonally adjusted 187.5 billion U.S. dollars, which is
expected to last at least three year, said the the department.
</P>
<P>
July's increase, the largest since November last year, followed
a 0.2 percent rise in June, which previously had been reported as
a 0.1 percent dip, and a 3.3 percent drop in May, the worst in
five months.
</P>
<P>
In July, orders growth was led by a 12 percent surge in
electrical and electronic equipment. A big increase in electronic
components more than offset a drop in communication equipment.
The category also includes radios, telephones, televisions, VCRs,
lamps, cooking equipment and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
Orders for industrial machinery and equipment, which includes
computers, rose 2 percent. Transportation orders rose 0.3 percent,
which was the first increase since April. A gain in aircraft and
parts offset declines in shipbuilding and auto manufacturing,
which was held back by the General Motors strikes, settled on July
25.
</P>
<P>
However, there was a 0.2 percent decline, the third in a row,
in orders for primary metals such as steel and aluminum.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of durable goods fell 0.2 percent in July, to a
seasonally adjusted 186.2 billion
dollars. It was the third drop in four months.
</P>
<P>
Because orders rose and shipments fell, the backlog of unfilled
orders rose 0.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted 506.2 billion
dollars, the first rise since April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
