<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Female Become Doctors in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- More women are filling
doctor's offices in Canada's hospitals and medical clinics,
statistics indicated Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 55,243 physicians practicing medicine in Canada last
year, a record 27.2 percent were women, up from 26.6 percent in
1996, statistics released by the Canadian Institute for Health
Information said.
</P>
<P>
Of doctors under 30 last year, 52.7 percent were women, while
female physicians only accounted for 40.6 percent of physicians in
their 30s.
</P>
<P>
The proportion was only 9.5 percent among the 6,721 Canadian
physicians for those in their 60s still practicing.
</P>
<P>
While women are flocking to what has been the male preserve of
medicine, they are tending to go into branches of the profession
involving careers in family practice, pediatrics, obstetrics and
gynecology, and psychiatry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
