<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Media Inundated With Flood Stories By Zhou Fang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Water, water, everywhere, and
not a drop to drink: China's television, radio, newspaper, and
magazine reporters have been engulfed by stories of the flooding
that has devastated parts of the country in the past two months,
the worst since 1954.
</P>
<P>
Water levels, evacuations, floodwaters, diversion, bursting
dikes, plugging dikes, and sandbags may have been unfamiliar to
younger readers, but they're everyday terms in these stories.
</P>
<P>
Stories about soldiers, police, and fighters, heros, and
victims of the flood have become daily fare across the
country. These instant legends told by the media day and night
have reduced some readers to tears with their heart-touching
descriptions.
</P>
<P>
China's floods and rescue work have drawn the attention of
people nationwide and even worldwide, and as a consequence, caused
a general mobilization of local media to cover everything
concerned, no matter how remote.
</P>
<P>
The major news media like Xinhua News Agency (Xinhua), People's
Daily, China Central Television (CCTV), and People's Liberation
Army Daily, as well as many other local media have gone all out in
their effort to keep readers informed about the flood situation,
the rescue efforts, the donations, and the daily lives of the
flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua's Department of Domestic News for Overseas Service,
together with CCTV's English Report, China Daily, China News
Service, Beijing Weekly Review, and other foreign-language
reporters in China have been doing a lot to cover the news from
every angle.
</P>
<P>
While millions of civilians and soldiers have been trying to
hold back floodwaters round-the-clock in northeastern, central and
eastern parts of the country, hundreds or even thousands of local
reporters have also kept their own round-the-clock watch on
water-logged dikes, inundated and crumbling residences, makeshift
shelters for victims, and of course the army of people fighting
the floods.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, some 200 reporters from Xinhua,
37 from People's Daily, nearly 400 from CCTV, 14 from Radio
Beijing, 37 from the PLA Daily, 25 from Economic Daily, and 32
from China Youth News have been sent to flooded areas. And
these are China's major players, the number of correspondents from
other media is simply too large to assess at this time.
</P>
<P>
Since July 24, Xinhua has released 2,859 flood-related stories
in six languages, with 750 photos, and the other media have had
their version of the same thing. But, television reports have the
most immediate appeal in the deluge of media coverage.
</P>
<P>
Live broadcasts of moving stories and performances for charity
benefits have been successful in getting people at home and abroad
to do their part in helping the relatives of the 3,004 people who
died in the floods, to share the woes of the flood's 22 million
victims, and to join the 230,000 soldiers who braved the raging
waters and in some cases even gave their lives to the largest
movement of military forces in China since 1949. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
