<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Tests Find Austrian Beef Hormone Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said on
Wednesday that it had found no trace of illegal hormones in
samples of Austrian beef.
</P>
<P>
The European Union Reference Laboratory at Bilthoven,
Netherlands, carried out tests on samples acquired from the
seizure by Italian authorities of a consignment of Austrian meat
last month.
</P>
<P>
The analysis of 17 of the 18 samples of Austrian beef proved to
be free of hormones diethylstilbestrol and dienestrol, said
commission officials.
</P>
<P>
One of the samples was rejected for technical reasons and tests
had to be repeated.
</P>
<P>
The Italian authorities said that the Austrian consignment of
beef had contained a banned hormone and alerted the European
Commission which thereafter conducted its own analysis.
</P>
<P>
Commission spokesperson Martine Reicherts said that the Italian
authorities had already lifted the ban on Austrian beef.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian farmers association said the health scare caused
by the Italian allegation had cost the country's beef industry
some 8 million U.S.dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
