<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Cyclist Suspended After Failing Drugs Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- British cyclist Gary Edwards has
been banned from England's Commonwealth Games team after failing
a drugs test, the British Cycling Federation (BCF) announced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The sprint cyclist from Ilford is reported to have breached
regulations governing testosterone levels in tests carried out by
the UK Sports Council.
</P>
<P>
Edwards returned testosterone/epitestosterone (t/e) ratios
above 6-1, requiring further analysis. Under doping regulations,
a 1-1 ratio is regarded as normal, while above 6-1, an offence
may have occurred.
</P>
<P>
The second or 'B' sample is being tested at King's College,
London, the only laboratory in Britain accredited by the
International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the BCF read: "In accordance with
Commonwealth Games Council regulations English sprint cyclist
Gary Edwards has been suspended from the English Commonwealth
Games team.
</P>
<P>
"The suspension follows a finding which warrants further
investigation not possible in the short period involved before
the Games commence."
</P>
<P>
Edwards, 32, returned to racing in Britain last year after a
spell in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Two other competitors, Paul Supple of England and Andrew
Goswell of Wales, are also reported to have produced "adverse
findings" in their tests and their participation in the
Commonwealth Games is also in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
Supple, the 94-kg weightlifter, was returned t/e ratios above
6-1 while Goswell, a 77-kg weightlifer, was found traces of
stanozolol, the anabolic steroid used by Canadian sprinter Ben
Johnson at the 1988 Olympics in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
If the second B samples did confirm the findings of the A
samples, then they would not be traveling to Kuala Lumpur,
capital city of Malaysia which plays host for the forthcoming
games next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
