<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Trade Outlook Bleak Despite Narrowing Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain's global trade deficit is
feared to worsen despite a narrowing in the trade gap in June and
July.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Office of National Statistics (ONS)
today show a narrowing of the global goods deficit in June to 1.44
billion pounds (about 2.3 billion U.S. dollars), down from a
revised 1.9 billion pounds in May.
</P>
<P>
The July deficit on goods trade with non-European countries
also narrowed slightly to 949 million pounds from 972 million
pounds in June.
</P>
<P>
Global trade in both goods and services was also in deficit for
June to the tune of 764 million pounds, but down from 1.2 billion
pounds the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Despite the narrowing, economists say the monthly figures are
erratic and further deterioration in the UK's trade performance in
coming months is expected.
</P>
<P>
The bleak picture for exports remains, with core export volumes
to non-EU countries now having fallen by 2 percent over the last
three months.
</P>
<P>
Further falls in exports are expected, matched by only marginal
falls in imports as the economy slows, a Commonwealth Bank analyst
said.
</P>
<P>
Neil Parker, economist at the Royal Bank of Scotland, pointed
to a narrowing in the surplus on services in July as a warning of
the deteriorating conditions for service exporters.
</P>
<P>
"That implies increasing competition from foreign providers,
who are selling relatively cheaper goods. It certainly doesn't
paint such a good picture for the UK trade balance," a BBC report
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Analysts broadly agreed that while there are signs of lower
import figures they do not provide clear evidence of demand
slowing enough to make for an easier interest rate climate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
