<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Group Denies Restaurant Blast Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- A Muslim group, which
reportedly claimed responsibility for Tuesday night's bombing in
a U.S.-franchised restaurant in Cape Town, South Africa, denied
Wednesday that it carried out the attack.
</P>
<P>
Moain Achmad, coordinator of the radical group, Muslims
Against Global Oppression (Mago), Wednesday denied that they
launched the bomb attack, in which one man was killed and 27
others were injured, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
A caller telephoned a Cape Town radio station Tuesday night
and claimed Mago was responsible for the blast, saying it was "a
job well done".
</P>
<P>
Achmad said anyone could call a radio station and claim
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
"They will try everything to discredit us... This bombing is a
way of stirring things up," Achmad said, without specifying whom
"they" were.
</P>
<P>
However, Achmad blamed the United States for the tragedy at
the Planet Hollywood restaurant at the Victoria and Alfred
Waterfront.
</P>
<P>
At grassroots level, he said, the situation was volatile
because U.S. President Bill Clinton had declared war on Muslims.
"He showed his arrogance by U.S. attacks in Afghanistan and
Sudan... Clinton must take full responsibility for what is
happening," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. forces launched missile attacks last week at alleged
terrorist camps in Afghanistan and Sudan. Clinton said the move
was not in retaliation for the deadly U.S. embassy bombings in
east Africa on August 7.
</P>
<P>
The Mago group, which vows to fight against "the Zionists and
their allies in the West", staged protests and burnt American
flags during Clinton's visit to South Africa in March this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
