<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Envoy Visits Libya Over Lockerbie Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President's envoy left
for Libya Wednesday for talks with Libyan leader Muammer Gaddafi
on a U.S.-British agreement over the Lockerbie bombing.
</P>
<P>
The trip of Osama el-Baz, President Hosni Mubarak's political
adviser, came after the U.S. and Britain announced on Monday their
proposal to allow two Libyans accused of involvement in the
Lockerbie bombing to be tried in a third country.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak held a telephone conversation Tuesday with Gaddafi over
the U.S.-British deal, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
But the agency did not give details of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced Monday
that the U.S. and Britain have agreed to allow the two Libyans,
who were charged with bombing a Pan Am flight in 1988 over
Lockerbie, Scotland, to be tried in The Hague, the Netherlands,
before Scottish judges under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
The Lockerbie incident killed 259 people aboard and 11 on the
ground at Lockerbie. Among the dead, 189 were Americans.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have long urged Libya to hand over the two
suspects to stand trial in either of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
But Libya refused to turn over the suspects, contending that
trial should be held to ensure its justness, which incurred the
U.N. air and arms embargo as well as certain financial and travel
restrictions in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan government has so far not commented on the
U.S.-British offer.
</P>
<P>
British officials said it is too early to expect a detailed
response from Libya to the proposal, but Albright has put the
proposal as non-negotiable by saying it was a "take it or leave it
proposition."
</P>
<P>
Egypt has described the deal as a "definite improvement,"
saying the issue is now in Libya's hands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Promises to Strengthen Business Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The German government and private
economy agreed Wednesday to make coordinated efforts to continue
business cooperation with Asia despite the region's financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The German foreign policy and the business world have a common
interest in supporting Asian countries' efforts to solve their
problems," said German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel and leaders
of the Asian-Pacific Committee of the German Economy after their
meeting Wednesday in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
In an action program agreed on at the meeting, German business
representatives also promised to explore new possibilities for
cooperation with Asian countries while seeking to strengthen and
expand existing ones.
</P>
<P>
They also called on Asian countries to push through necessary
economic reforms and to reduce state regulations.  
</P>
