<HEADLINE> Bank of Greece Intervenes Heavily in Domestic Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Greece's central bank, the Bank
of Greece, intervened heavily in the domestic markets Wednesday by
spending 1.2 billion U.S. dollars to defend the bond market and
the drachma in the face of pressure from a deepening financial
crisis in Russia and other developing markets.
</P>
<P>
Foreign institutional investors reportedly preferred to
liquidate their substantial gains in the Greek bond market in an
effort to hedge their losses in other international markets, the
semi- official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Greek national currency's parity was significant lower
against most foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
The drachma was 1.48 percent lower against the U.S. dollar, 1.0
percent off against the mark and 1.07 percent lower against the
ecu.
</P>
<P>
One-month interbank rates also climbed above 14 percent for the
first time in several months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
