<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran has produced 145,000 cars and 1,000 heavy
automobiles so far from the beginning of the current Iranian year
(starting from March 21), Deputy Minister of Industries Ali Seyed
Abrishami announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Abrishami said that the country expects to produce 290,000
cars, 3,000 heavy trucks and buses as well as 3,000 mini-buses in
this Iranian year and to export some of the products to Russia,
Yemen and some African countries.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- A seminar on business opportunities in Israel will
be held in Cyprus early next month.
</P>
<P>
According to an official announcement here Wednesday, among
the issues to be discussed are "business prospects in Israel,"
"Cyprus as a bridge toward Europe" and "prime minister's business
summit in Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem summit, to take place from October 13-15, will
provide businessmen with the opportunity to exchange views on
matters of mutual interest, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Chairman of Egypt's "Nasr Television" company Sami
Bayoumi said the company Tuesday signed a contract to the tune of
46 million U.S. dollars with the Korean Daewoo company for the
purchase of component part for 20,000 color TV sets of 14, 16, 20
and 29 inches over the coming two years.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Arab daily "Al Hayat" reported that Daewoo is
exporting about 40,000 TV sets a year to Egypt's "Benha Electric
Industries" company. As a matter of fact, the TV market in Egypt
absorbs 520,000 TV sets a year.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- An official source in the Yemeni Ministry of Oil and
Mineral Resources anticipates that the fall in petroleum prices
will lead to the shrinking of Yemeni oil revenues to 650 million
U.S. dollars this year, compared with 1.2 billion dollars of last
year, the latest edition of Yemeni weekly newspaper "Al Wihda"
reported.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian exports to Canada more than doubled in the
first five months of 1998 than that of the same period of last
year despite the devaluation of the Canadian dollar against the
U.S. dollar, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the January-May period, sweets exports increased by 700
percent, conserved food products by 548 percent, clothes 163
percent, iron and steel 106 percent, fresh, dried and conserved
fruits by 72 percent, according to a report prepared by the
Ministry of Trade and Supply.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egyptian imports from canada were down by 15.8
percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A recent report by the American-Egyptian Chamber of
Commerce said there are over 1 billion dollars invested annually
in Egypt and that about 500 leading foreign joint ventures are
working in the fields of oil, banking, tourism and other
industrial sectors, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said that economic liberalization and privatization in the
country attracted foreign and local investments in one of the most
promising markets in the world at present.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the private sector share in the gross
domestic product rose from 61.8 percent in the 1992/93 fiscal
year to 66.4 percent in 1996/97. 
</P>
</TEXT>
