<HEADLINE> Simitis, Kostov Hold Talks Over Economic Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis said Wednesday that Greece and Bulgaria were getting
nearer to attaining their common objective - excellent
communication.
</P>
<P>
After meeting his visiting Bulgarian counterpart, Ivan Kostov,
Simitis told reporters that relations between the two countries
were "at a good level," and any problems which did rise were
effectively dealt with.
</P>
<P>
Both men discussed the planned Burgas-Alexandroupolis oil
pipeline, the nuclear plant at Kozloduy in Bulgaria, road
connections along the Greek-Bulgarian border, cooperation in the
customs sector, the avoidance of double taxation and matters
regarding visa requirements.
</P>
<P>
As for the oil pipeline, Simitis said that both sides agreed
that Bulgaria must put certain questions to the Russian side about
matters requiring some clarification and then they would examine
any problems which there might be.
</P>
<P>
On the Kozloduy nuclear plant, he said that Kostov had supplied
a series of data, on the basis of which the Greek atomic energy
commission would examine any problems which might exist.
</P>
<P>
He expressed satisfaction over the progress in the construction
of road connections along the Greek-Bulgarian border and added
that the two countries would be working closely to combat
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also announced that the possibility would be
examined of creating a free movement zone to a depth of 25
kilometers on either side of the Greek-Bulgarian border.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Kostov, who is in Greece for a one-day working
visit, described his talks with Simitis as "positive," saying that
both countries were ready to make further efforts to develop
bilateral ties through open contacts.
</P>
<P>
He also thanked Athens for its assistance in Sofia's efforts to
join the European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
