<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libya Asks U.N. for More Time to Study Lockerbie Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Libya has asked the U.N.
Security Council to delay its decision on a draft resolution
introduced by the United States and Britain, so that Tripoli can
have more time to study the U.S.-UK proposal on the trial of the
two Lockerbie suspects in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, told reporters on Wednesday
that the Libyan request was contained in a letter, which was made
public here Wednesday. The letter, dated August 25, represented
the first official response from the Libyan Government on the
Lockerbie trial offer.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that "a decision on the draft resolution
presented to the Security Council be postponed until Libya's
judicial authorities have completed their study."
</P>
<P>
Such a postponement would ensure that "the two suspects appear
in a court in a neutral third country as soon as possible," the
letter said.
</P>
<P>
"Libya is anxious to arrive at a settlement of this dispute and
to turn over a new page in its relations with the states
concerned," said the letter, which was sent to Security Council
members late on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The letter said Tripoli was "very surprised" to see the draft
resolution on the Lockerbie issue even though it had only received
papers on Monday from Washington and London detailing their offer
on holding a Scottishh court trial of the two Libyan suspects in
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council would consider the letter, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Washington and London offered to try the two
suspects by a panel of three Scottish judges under Scottish law in
the Netherlands. Before the compromise, the United States and
Britain had long insisted the trial be held on either of their
territories.
</P>
<P>
The two suspects were accused of planting a bomb aboard the an
American airliner, which exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland, in
December 1988, killing about 270 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0026 </DOCNO>
