The ruling African National Congress (ANC) and the Inkatha
Freedom Party (IFP), the biggest black opposition party in the
country, condemned the bombing Wednesday, saying it was
terroristic and cowardly attack on innocent victims.
</P>
<P>
The ANC said the bombing and other recent pipe bomb attacks
in Cape Town, which had claimed a number of lives, should be
attended to expeditiously by the law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
Ebrahim Rasool, ANC's provincial leader in Western Cape,
where Cape Town is located, visited the bomb scene Wednesday.
"It's not a time for cheap politics, but a time for cooperation
from national level to provincial level along with
non-governmental people, in fact, everyone," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IFP said: "whatever objective anyone had is sullied by
this cowardly attack on civilians who did not deserve to have
their lives destroyed."
</P>
<P>
The United Democratic Movement (UDM) and the Freedom Front
(FF), two other opposition parties, urged the government to take
tougher action against criminals.
</P>
<P>
The UDM said the government needed to adopt a zero-tolerance
attitude toward crime and violence, while the FF called for
reintroduction of the death penalty to deter murderers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. embassy in Pretoria recommended that
American citizens take special precautions to ensure their
personal safety.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident the South African Police Service will move
quickly to identify and apprehend those responsible for this
disgusting act," the embassy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Safety and Security Minister Sidney Mufamadi, who visited the
scene, linked the bomb to the August 7 blasts at U.S.
installations in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
He said there was a strong likelihood "local operatives" had
been used in the interests of international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
A Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) team was en route to
Cape Town Wednesday to help investigate the blast. The FBI agents
would probe whether the bombing was related to the attacks in
Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Police Commissioner George Fivaz said that with the aid of
U.S. explosive experts, he expects arrests soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, worries were expressed over the bombing's impact
on tourism in the country. A Cape Town metropolitan official
said the incident would have "serious long term repercussions"
for Cape Town's thriving tourist market.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that Cape Town has been made a target for
what would appear to be anti-U.S. terrorism," he said. He called
on all Capetonians to make efforts to protect their most valuable
industry - tourism - by ensuring all visitors feel safe in the
city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
