<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Vows to Protect Northern Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Israel's inner cabinet vowed
Wednesday to defend its residents in northern areas following the
most serious rocket attacks on Israeli northern towns by Lebanon's
Hezbollah guerillas in months.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after its meeting, the Israeli inner
cabinet said that it viewed the rocket attacks on Tuesday night as
a "grave violation" of the understandings reached in 1996 which
banned both sides from hitting civilians.
</P>
<P>
Israel will continue to strike terrorist organizations and act
to defend its residents in the north and restore security to the
northern border, the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Life returned to normal Wednesday in the northern Israeli town
of Kiryat Shmona and parts of Western Galilee, where at least 14
people were lightly wounded or suffered from shock after the
Hezbollah guerillas fired dozens of Katyusha rockets there Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to the northern areas Wednesday, Israeli
President Ezer Weizman reiterated that the problem Israel faces
in south Lebanon would not be resolved without a role of Syria,
calling for the resumption of the Israeli-Syrian talks, which
broke off in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah attacks were apparently in response to the
missile strike by an Israeli military airplane earlier Tuesday
that killed Husam Amin, regional chief of Amal operations, the
second largest military organization which fights to oust Israeli
troops out of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Labor Party leader Ehud Barak expressed his support
Wednesday for the decision to attack Amin, but stressed that the
only solution to the conflict in the north is to revive direct
talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
However, Uzi Landau, chairman of the Foreign Affairs and
Defense Committee in Israel's parliament, said Israel should
strike Syrian forces in Lebanon which he accused of using the
means of terrorism to try to force Israel to withdraw from the
Golan Heights, seized by Israel from Syria in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's shelling came at a time when tension flared up in the
so-called security zone in south Lebanon, set up by Israel in 1985
with an aim to protect its northern areas from cross-border
attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli soldiers and one civilian employed by the army,
were killed by roadside bombs last week, bringing to 12 the
number of the Israelis who were killed in the 15-kilometer-deep
security zone since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
Under heavy pressure from the Israeli public, the Israeli
government adopted in April the 20-year-old United Nations
Resolution 425 calling on Israel to withdraw its troops from
south Lebanon, but linked the pullout to security arrangements
from the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its main ally Syria have rejected the proposal on
the ground that the resolution calls for an "immediate and
unconditional" Israeli troop withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
