<HEADLINE> UNICEF Reports Declining of Malnourished Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) said on Wednesday that the incidence of
malnourished children appeared to be declining in certain parts of
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
UNICEF said in a statement the situation had improved in
accessible areas. According to the United Nations Agency, its
staff reported seeing declining numbers of malnourished children
during field visits this year.
</P>
<P>
The agency also reported improvement in the health sector,
saying hospital records made available to it generally indicated
reductions in fatality and improvement in the rehabilitation of
patients.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF said it continued its activities to assist those
affected by food shortages and to rebuild essential health, water,
food security and education system in the country.
</P>
<P>
It added that it was currently delivering drugs, medical
equipment and water and sanitation supplies to an estimated 4.6
million people, including 500,000 children under the age of five
years, which was aimed at both immediate and long-term needs in
the country.  
</P>
