<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus: Delay in Russian Missiles' Delivery Not </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said Wednesday that no decisions have been taken
regarding a possible postponement of the arrival of Russian
anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Larnaca Airport before his departure to Athens for
talks with Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis, Clerides said
"even if such a decision is taken, it will be taken in Cyprus by
the National Council."
</P>
<P>
The National Council, the top advisory body to the president on
the handling of the Cyprus problem, has insisted on the deployment
of the missiles unless there is sufficient progress toward a
resolution of the Cyprus problem or the situation moves leading to
the demilitarization of the island.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered the surface-to-air S-300
missiles from Russia in January 1997 in a bid to boost the
country's air defense as against a possible Turkish offensive. The
missiles are scheduled to be delivered and deployed in November
this year.
</P>
<P>
The deal has sparked strong protests from Turkey, which vowed
to block the arrival of the missiles and threatened to launch
preemptive strikes if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
There have been wide speculations here that during the Athens
meeting, the Cypriot and Greek leaders will discuss the
possibility of postponing the deployment of the missiles in light
of political pressure from some foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said that during Thursday's meeting in Athens, there
will be "an exchange of views on the current position of the
Cyprus problem, future handling, the island's European Union
accession course, the joint defense pact between Cyprus and
Greece, armaments and the Russian S-300 missiles."
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be attended by Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides and Defense Minister Yiannakis Omirou.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece signed the joint defense pact in November
1993, under which Greece will provide military assistance in case
Cyprus is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and seized the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
From Athens, Clerides will fly to Durban, South Africa, to
attend the Non-Aligned Movement summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
