<HEADLINE> Syrian Fishermen Convicted in Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Seven Syrian fishermen were
sentenced to one-month in prison by the Turkish Cypriot regime
after they were caught fishing off the Cyprus' eastern coast.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen, captured last Friday, were convicted Tuesday,
Turkish Cypriot press and radio reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the jail term was granted, instead of a
fine, in a bid to prevent more Syrian fishermen from entering the
waters that the Turkish Cypriot regime claims under its control.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian embassy in Nicosia said Wednesday that it is working
to get the details about the incident.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time that the Turkish Cypriot regime has
caught Syrian fishermen.
</P>
<P>
One fisherman was shot dead and three others captured by
Turkish Cypriot armymen in April 1995.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island in the wake of failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is recognized
only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
