<HEADLINE> Lawyers Vow to Pursue Lawsuits against European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Lawyers for Holocaust survivors
Wednesday said they would pursue the class-action lawsuits against
European insurance companies despite a compromise deal reached
Tuesday in New York.
</P>
<P>
Leading European insurance companies signed an agreement
Tuesday in New York in a bid to resolve the dispute over unpaid
Nazi-era insurance policies of Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum of understanding, negotiated by the World Jewish
Congress, the U.S. insurance regulators and European insurance
companies, establishes an international commission that would
examine the insurance companies' achives, set up a process to
resolve claims and determine a company's liability.
</P>
<P>
However, Michael Witti, a Munich lawyer who represents
thousands of Holocaust survivors, sharply criticized the deal on
Wednesday, saying that the insurance companies wanted to get off
more lightly and cheaply by excluding Holocaust survivors from
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"Even the Jewish organizations do not have the right to make
the decision for the claimants," Witti said.
</P>
<P>
Some other lawyers have also expressed objection to the
agreement, noting that it was not legally-binding and did not
guarantee quick payment of policies.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to pursue our class-action lawsuit
vigorously," said Witti in reference to a billions-of-dollar legal
action launched by Holocaust survivors against 16 European
insurers last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile he also indicated that a out-of-court deal with the
insurance companies was still possible, but with the involvement
of Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
Allianz AG, Germany's largest insurance company which signed
the New York accord, on Wednesday dismissed the accusations made
by the lawyers. It also expressed the hope that the New York
agreement would make the legal action unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
Other major European insurance companies which signed the
agreement include the French company AXA Group, the Swiss
companies Winterthur and Baseler, and Der Anker of Austria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Manufacturing Hits 5-Year Low to Herald Growth Halt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- With Britain's manufacturing
hitting a five-year low, the Confederation of British Industry
(CBI) has predicted the UK economy will "grind to a halt" by
mid-1999 and called for a quick cut in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In its latest monthly Industrial Trends survey showing
manufacturing orders at a five-and-a-half-year low, the CBI
downgraded its forecasts for overall economic growth but said it
still expected a "soft landing".
</P>
<P>
"We now expect economic growth over the next three quarters
will almost grind to a halt, so we believe an early cut in
interest rates is vital to prevent the economy slipping further
than necessary," CBI's chief economic adviser, Kate Barker, said,
adding that it would still be possible for the Government's
inflation target to be met after an interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
The CBI predicted Gross Domestic Product, the main measure of
economic growth, to fall to 1.5 percent by the end of the year and
0.9 percent by mid-1999 before climbing back to 1.5 percent by the
end of next year. That is supposed to broadly describe the "soft
landing" for the economy the government and the Bank of England
have predicted.
</P>
<P>
The CBI said it expected official interest rates to fall 0.25
percent to 7.25 percent by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
It said while a hard landing is not expected, there are more
risks of the economy stalling than last May with the problems
facing the export sector having a knock-on effect in the domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
Total orders for British manufacturers hit their lowest level
in more than five years with 41 percent of firms reporting order
books below normal while only 10 percent said orders were above
normal.
</P>
<P>
This gives an overall negative balance of minus 31 percent,
unchanged from July and worse than June's minus 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the survey showed export orders slipping back to
their levels of May, which were the lowest since 1983. The export
orders balance was at minus 51 percent, slightly worse than
previous months while the output expectations balance stood at
minus 15 percent this month compared to minus 8 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
There is no sign of the recessionary pressure easing on UK
manufacturers, the CBI said.
</P>
<P>
The latest economic statistics showing record mortgage lending
on one hand and five-year lows in manufacturing orders on the
other confirm widely differing conditions across the British
economy, economists said.
</P>
<P>
The UK home lending market remains buoyant with mortgage
lending jumping to a record 5.7 billion pounds (about 9.1 billion
U.S. dollars) in July, according to figures released by the
British Bankers' Association (BBA). That was 14 percent higher
than June lending, confirming the housing sector as one area of
the economy maintaining strong growth.
</P>
<P>
The two sets of figures provide more evidence of the so-called
"two-speed" British economy with some areas, like housing and
services, experiencing continuing growth while others, like
manufacturing, slip into recession.
</P>
<P>
This varied performance makes it harder for the Bank of England
to judge the appropriate level of interest rates as it attempts to
engineer a "soft landing" for the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
