<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Urges Withdrawal From South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Israel must make quick
decisions both on its withdrawal from south Lebanon and on the
redeployment in the West Bank, Israeli Public Security Minister
Avigdor Kahalani said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Kahalani said an Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon should be the "number one strategic
priority" for the government.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani's remarks on south Lebanon came as tensions
intensified recently in south Lebanon with stepped-up clashes
between Israeli troops and Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer "security zone" in
south Lebanon in 1985 to protect northern areas from cross-border
attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
But there has been a strong call in Israel for withdrawal from
the zone due to the heavy human losses in fightings with the
resistance.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani also noted both Lebanon and Syria should be involved
if a solution is to be found.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman and other senior officials have
stressed recently that a solution to the south Lebanon problem can
be found without the involvement of Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria, who has great influence on Lebanon, opposes an Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon without an agreement on the return
of the Golan Heights, which was captured by Israel in the 1967
Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel offered to pull back from south Lebanon in
exchange of Lebanese security guarantee of its northern areas. But
Lebanon and Syria firmly rejected the offer, saying that Israel
should withdraw from south Lebanon unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the redeployment in the West Bank, the
minister said he believed that an agreement would be reached
around the beginning of a series of Jewish holidays late next
month, urging both Israel and the Palestinians to show
flexibility in their talks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel resumed direct talks on July 19 to
discuss a U.S. proposal, which calls for a 13 percent Israeli
troops withdrawal from the West Bank. There are reports indicating
certain progress could have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
