<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Leauge Hails Libya's Flexibility on Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Esmat Abdel Meguid said Thursday that the Libyan consent to the
U.S.-British proposal on settling the Lockerbie issue is an
"important step along the road to end this problem for good."
</P>
<P>
Abdel Meguid, who is now in Lebanon, told Egypt's Middle East
News Agency that Libya's acceptance of the proposal was "expected"
as the proposal was in line with Libya's stance and an idea
presented by the AL three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Libya Wednesday accepted a joint U.S.-British proposal that the
two Libyan suspects in the 1988 bombing of an American plane be
tried by a panel of three Scottish judges under Scottish law in
the Hague, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have long urged Libya to hand over the two
suspects to stand trial in either of the two countries. But Libya
refused to turn over the suspects, contending that the trial
should be held in a third country to ensure justice.
</P>
<P>
"Libya's stand is flexible," Abdel Meguid said, urging the
United Nations to remove the six-year-old sanctions imposed on
Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
The air embargo and arms sales, certain financial and travel
restrictions were imposed in 1992 after Libya refused to hand over
the two suspects, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa
Fhimah. The bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland, killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
"I expect that the Security Council will take a step towards
lifting the international sanctions imposed against Libya
immediately after the two suspects are handed over," said Abdel
Meguid.
</P>
<P>
But he added that this issue has not yet been settled and will
be crystalized through negotiations in the coming period.
</P>
<P>
For the second consecutive day, the Security Council Thursday
met to consider a draft resolution sponsored by the U.S. and
Britain to suspend U.N. sanctions on Libya when the suspects
arrive in the Netherlands for trial.
</P>
<P>
"There will be intensive and hard work for guaranteeing a fair
trial of the two suspects. And this will be our mission in the
coming stage," said the AL chief, who noted that the Cairo-based
Arab forum is willing to play any role to settle the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Bank Raises Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Canada's central bank raised
interest rates by a full point to six percent Thursday in a
desperate move to prop up its currency.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Canadian dollar made a new record
Wednesday, dropping for the first time in its 140-year history
below 64 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
During the past six months, the Canadian dollar lost about 10
percent of its value against the strong U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
With the rate hike, the bank's operating band for the overnight
rate was similarly adjusted to a range of five to six percent.
</P>
<P>
"Today's increase in interest rates is aimed at providing
support for the Canadian dollar in order to bolster confidence,
while preserving monetary conditions that will help to sustain the
present non-inflationary expansion of the economy," the bank said
in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
