<HEADLINE> India Sharply Raises Postal Services Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Union government
Thursday announced a sharp increase of up to 150 percent of postal
charges with effect from the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
This is the second hike in postal services this year. The
tariff of post covers, competition post cards and letter cards had
gone up by 50 percent each, while parcel and insurance charges by
25 percent and registration charges by 20 percent following an
announcement by Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha while presenting
the 1998-99 budget on June 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The increased postal tariff would lead to an additional annual
revenue of 2,700 million rupees (64.29 million U.S. dollars),
leaving behind an uncovered postal deficit of 6,950 million rupees
(165.48 million dollars), an official release said.
</P>
<P>
Ordinary post cards and inland letters have been spared from
the hike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
