<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Says FPDA Exercise To Be Abandoned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Ministry of Defense
Thursday confirmed that a major maritime and air exercise
scheduled for later this year by allies of the Five-Power Defense
Arrangements (FPDA) will be abandoned because Malaysia has decided
to pull out from it.
</P>
<P>
In a press release to respond press queries, the ministry said,
"as a consequence of Malaysia's decision, Exercise Stardex, a
major maritime and air exercise scheduled for September/October
1998 will not be able to proceed."
</P>
<P>
"As ships of the Australian, New Zealand and the United Kingdom
forces have already commenced deployment to this region for
Exercise Stardex, Singapore will do its best to accommodate
requests for ad hoc training activities and professional exchanges
with these forces in order to help them derive the most value from
their deployment to this region," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
But it reaffirmed that Singapore stands firm on its belief that
 the FPDA is of strategic importance to regional stability and
regular FPDA exercises are useful.
</P>
<P>
"This view remains unchanged," the ministry emphasized.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to continue with the full range of FPDA
activities when Malaysia is able to do so," the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers reported that Malaysian Defense Minister Syed
Hamid Albar announced earlier in an interview with the Far East
Economic Review that Malaysia has decided to pull out from FPDA
exercises slated for this year because of its economic woes and
intense relations with Singapore. The defense minister was also
quoted as saying that Malaysia has informed other FPDA members of
its decision.
</P>
<P>
The FPDA has existed for 27 years as a military alliance
between Australia, Malaysia, New Zealand, Singapore and the United
Kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
