<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A five-day grape festival opened
today in Turpan in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
This is the city's 8th festival, and a number of theatrical
performances are planned for tourists, and economic and trade
talks are being held by the local government.
</P>
<P>
Turpan is an ancient city on the Silk Road and a political,
economic and cultural center for China's western parts in the old
days. It was one of the first cities in the region approved in
1978 by the State Council for opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to its grape festivals, Turpan had formed connections
with many provinces, regions, and cities in China and with more
than 140 countries, leading to more than 70 cooperative projects
set up in the city. 
