<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea Orders 13 Banks to Improve Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
Thursday ordered 13 banks to improve their capital standings
despite their capital adequacy ratios exceeding the international
level of eight percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Supervisory Commission Thursday said the 13 banks
considered financially stable have showed financial inadequacy
when their standings were evaluated in accordance with tougher
standards of the Office of Bank Supervision.
</P>
<P>
The 13 banks' capital ratio went beyond the eight percent level
set by the Bank for International Settlements and some even hit 13
percent in previous evaluations of the Office of Bank Supervision.
</P>
<P>
However, most of the 13 banks fell below the required standard
of eight percent in revised evaluations by the Office of Bank
Supervision and some even registered negative standings under new
international criteria, said the commission.
</P>
<P>
Recent evaluations showed that the 13 banks, with big
investments in overseas and trust accounts and leasing affiliates,
suffered the greatest falls in the ratio of the Bank of
International Settlement.
</P>
<P>
In order to survive and develop under tougher local and
international evaluation standards, the banks have to reduce
outlets and staff, to undergo major restructuring by seeking
mergers and foreign investments, said the commission.
</P>
<P>
The government's financial watchdog said it will start
evaluation on the 13 banks this month to check whether their June
BIS ratio exceeds eight percent and will issue improvement orders
on those who fail.
</P>
<P>
The 13 South Korean banks are Housing and Commercial, Kookmin,
Shinhan, KorAm, Hana, Boram, Daegu, Pusan, Kwangju, Cheju,
Jeonbuk, Kyungnam and Korea Long-Term Credit Bank.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has ordered closure of 14 ailing commercial and
merchant banks since the country was hit by a financial crisis
caused by corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial
institutions late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taylor Admits Failure in 1st Year in Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles Taylor
has admitted that he has failed to deliver on election promises
during his first year in office, a report by the Inter Press
Service said.
</P>
<P>
"I have failed my first year. I have not been able to do what
I should have done in my first year in office. Many of the high
expectations... have not been met. Our agriculture is ravaged,
our infrastructure is ruined and our people are devastated and
disappointed," Taylor said on his first anniversary in office.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to his country's 2.8 million people to give him
another chance.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, who started the Liberian civil war in 1989, began his
six-year term of office on August 2, 1997, when he won 75 percent
of the vote in an election organized by the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS) to end more than seven years of
civil war.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said then that Liberians voted for Taylor for fear
that if he lost, the most powerful warlords in the bloody civil
war might choose not to give peace to the country.
</P>
<P>
"The man who spoiled it should fix it," the voters sang during
last year's elections campaign, referring to Taylor. "He killed
my ma, he killed my pah, I will vote for him."
</P>
<P>
Taylor promised to restore everything Liberians had lost
during the war. He promised a true national reconciliation,
restoring electricity and running water and even a computer for
every Liberian child.
</P>
<P>
He attributed his failure to "unexplainable delays and global
empty promises" on the part of the international community in
helping Liberia in its post-war reconstruction efforts.
</P>
<P>
A major donor conference held in Paris in April pledged 220
million U.S. Dollars for Liberia's reconstruction program. But
only a few countries have made small financial packages since
then.
</P>
<P>
One of them, the United States, has provided 55 million
Dollars, but to the chagrin of the Liberian government, the
packages are being channeled through non-governmental
organizations (NGOs).
</P>
<P>
Now one year after Taylor took office, Liberians have remained
without clean running water, electricity, adequate security,
regular decent meals and houses.
</P>
<P>
"The sweat-drenched euphoria (generated shortly before and
after last year's polls) has given way to tougher times... with
almost everybody, if not all, feeling the pinch and wearing grim
and melancholic faces," said Liberia's independent newspaper,
Heritage.
</P>
<P>
Prices of basic commodities, too, have hit the sky in a
country where salaries range between 80 Liberia Dollars (two U.S.
Dollars) to 850 Liberia Dollars (21 U.S. Dollars) a month, while
a gallon of gasoline now sells for 65 Liberia Dollars (about 1.6
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Both the agriculture sector, which feeds 75 percent of the
population, and the iron ore mining industry, which accounted for
70 percent of Liberia's hard currency earnings before the war,
have been slow in recovery.
</P>
<P>
Security, too, has remained a major issue of concern.
"Security agents are harassing us day and night," complained
Chief Elijah Nagbe, at a recent conference in neighboring Cote
d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
The murder of one of Taylor's rivals, Samuel Dokie, last year,
has cast a shadow over the so called true reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Dokie, together with his wife, sister, cousin and driver were
arrested by government security agents and subsequently found
burnt to death in the car they were traveling in. Suspects were
freed by a court for lack of evidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
