<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi FM on Border Clash With India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Abdus
Samad Azad on Thursday described as a "serious matter" the border
clash between Bangladesh and India on Tuesday that left at least
one Bangladesh Rifles (BDR) personnel dead.
</P>
<P>
"There was a firing incident at the border on August 25
resulting in the death of a BDR personnel. This is a serious
matter and is being taken up bilaterally through normal channel
with the concerned Indian authorities," Azad said at a regular
weekly press briefing.
</P>
<P>
But he parried a question if the government had formally lodged
any protest with the Indian government in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Azad gave the reaction two days after the Indian Border
Security Force (BSF) and the BDR clashed in Dinajpur district,
northwest Bangladesh, over rebuilding a frontier wall at the "zero
point" by the BSF. In the clash, one BDR soldier was reportedly
killed and many others wounded.
</P>
<P>
A meeting between the border security forces of the two
countries was held Wednesday, he said, adding, "We are waiting for
the details."
</P>
<P>
"Problems, even serious problems, if and when they arise, can
and should be addressed and resolved through discussion and
dialogue," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
On the existing relations between Dhaka and New Delhi, he said
that "we attach great importance to the friendly and good
relations with India and nothing should be allowed to detract from
this objective." 
