<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Fishermen Threaten Blockade of Cruise Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Canadian salmon fishermen have
threatened to blockade the West Coast cruise-ship route, the Globe
and Mail newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The West Coast salmon fleet has caught barely 50 percent of
what was predicted before the season opened this year, and
conservation measures have effectively brought it to a premature
close.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall means a loss of tens of millions of dollars and
makes this season the worst in the history of the province of
British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
The plan to conserve a resource endangered by past overfishing
and habitat destruction, plus unusual climate conditions will
produce a catch of barely 4.5 million salmon this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 fishing boats staged a noisy two-hour symbolic
blockade Wednesday, although no cruise ships were stopped. But
fishermen involved said they would make it permanent if the
government rejected all their demands.
</P>
<P>
The protesters have issued a list of demands, including a
face-to-face meeting with federal Fisheries Minister David
Anderson and cash compensation for fish lost through what they
claim is departmental mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Nine Alaska-bound cruise ships are scheduled to sail through
the passage by Monday. Cruise ships will make 300 Alaska-bound
trips from Vancouver this summer, carrying 800,000 passengers in
an industry that brings 200 million Canadian dollars (128 million
U.S. dollars) to the British Columbia economy.
</P>
<P>
A blockade would require cruise ships to make a 450-kilometer
diversion around Vancouver Island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0075 </DOCNO>
