<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheung Kong, Hutchison Whampoa Report Lower Interim Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Cheung Kong (Holdings) and
Hutchison Whampoa, the listed flagships of Li Ka-shing, reported
significantly lower first-half results Thursday, reflecting the
adverse impact of the regional financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Both groups made heavy provisions against the fall in the value
of properties and listed securities.
</P>
<P>
After exceptional provisions of 3.435 billion HK dollars (440
million U.S. dollars), Cheung Kong (Holdings) saw its profit
attributable to shareholders plunge by 78 percent to 3.023 billion
HK dollars (388 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Hutchison Whampoa's net profit amounted to 4.310 billion HK
dollars (553 million U.S. dollars) in the first half, down 45
percent from last year. The diversified and increasingly
international group made exceptional provisions of 3.450 billion
HK dollars (442 million U.S. dollars) for certain property
developments and its portfolio of listed investments.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of both groups Li Ka-shing told a press conference
Thursday afternoon that the interim results have been achieved
during a period of continued turmoil in the Asian financial
market, which has adversely affected Hong Kong property market and
 economy.
</P>
<P>
The remainder of the 1998 will continue to be difficult and
challenging and under the circumstances provisions are necessary,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The businessman predicted that "the possibility of a further
plunge in property prices is limited" following successive
adjustments in the market and government measures to bolster the
economy and stabilize the property market.
</P>
<P>
Supported by strong demand for property, the long-term
prospects for the property sector remain optimistic, provided that
confidence is restored, Li noted.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the long-term prospects of Hong Kong economy, he was
fully optimistic. On the back of steady economic progress in the
Chinese mainland, Hong Kong is well positioned to consolidate its
role as a financial, trade and service center in the region, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Li added that his companies will continue to be based in Hong
Kong and pursue suitable investments in Hong Kong, the Chinese
mainland and overseas in a prudent manner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
