<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Loan Earmarked for S. Korean Small Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government is to
provide six trillion won (4.19 billion U.S. dollars) for small
businesses this year in bid to bolster the flagging economy.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance and Economy Lee Kyu-sung told company
managers at a meeting Thursday that the government will disburse
all of the remaining six trillion won out of the 12.5 trillion-won
earmarked for small businesses this year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
"The government will do its best to prevent the aggravation of
recession and restore financial systems," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry would take strong pump-priming measures, such as
rolling over short-term debt, rescheduling other debts and writing
off the remaining liabilities, for small-sized firms, he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 17,000 small firms have been bankrupt since the
country was gripped by a financial crisis triggered by corporate
failures and bad loans by financial institutions late last year.
</P>
<P>
The minister also disclosed that the government would increase
money supply as flexibly as possible in the second half of this
year under an accord with the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
To help ease debt burden on businesses, he said, the ministry
would also try to further lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will embark on large public works and
social infrastructure projects as planned to create more jobs
right after the National Assembly approves its second revised
supplementary budget next month, he added.
</P>
<P>
In June this year, unemployment in South Korea soared to seven
percent or 1.57 million people since the country was hit by the
financial crisis. The jobless rate is expected to grow as
restructuring in the finance, industry, labor markets and the
public sector will continue until next year.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed with the IMF for a rescue loan of 58
billion U.S. dollars, South Korea has to restructure its economy
and open its markets this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
