<HEADLINE> EU Inactive But Watchful As Ruble Falls Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said on
Thursday that it will wait until next Thursday before considering
action on Russia's worsening financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The executive body of the 15-nation European Union admitted it
was doing nothing more than just watch on a "daily basis" or "as
closely as possible" for the time being over developments in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Commission spokesperson Martine Reicherts said that the
commission was scheduled to resume after the summer recess its
weekly meetings next Thursday, one day later than usual, as some
commissioners including President Jacques Santer would be away in
Lisbon for European Day.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the commission was concerned by the pressure
of the freefall of the Russian currency, the spokesperson said
that it was as concerned as the European Central Bank which is now
in operation in Frankfurt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
But commission officials said earlier this week that the
commission had no plans yet for extra financial assistance to
Russia except for the existing TACIS technical aid program.
</P>
<P>
The commission said time and again that the financial crisis
was a problem for the Russians who had to do what they could to
bail themselves out and that outside assistance would only help
with action by the Russians.
</P>
<P>
Losses by foreign investors in Russian bonds reportedly
amounted to 33 billion U.S. dollars by Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
