<HEADLINE> SADC Ministers Consult with OAU Chief on Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) ministerial delegation left here
Thursday after two-day consultations with the OAU chief on the
situation in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
An OAU press release issued here Thursday said Salim Ahmed
Salim, the secretary-general of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU), and the delegation led by South African Foreign Minister
Alfred Nzo expressed concern over the gravity of the unfolding
situation in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"They stressed the importance of finding a speedy political
solution to the current conflict in the Congo, emphasizing that
such a solution is in the best interest of the Congolese people,
the region and the continent as a whole," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Both the delegation and the OAU chief underscored the urgent
need for securing a an end to the hostilities through a
ceasefire, a troop standstill and an initiation of a peaceful
process of political dialog as provided for in the Pretoria
communique of the SADC summit held on August 23, said the
release.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also exchanged views on the best ways and means
for the implementation of the Pretoria communique, particularly
the provision calling for the setting up of mechanisms for its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the need for intensive consultations among the
leaders of the region with a view to attaining an immediate
ceasefire, according to the release.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they agreed that more time was needed for further
consultation prior to the dispatch of a delegation to the parties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
The SADC ministerial delegation which also comprised foreign
ministers from Tanzania, Mozambique and Zambia as well as South
African defense minister, arrived here Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
