<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Economy Declines 6.8 PCT in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's economic growth
declined by 6.8 percent in the second quarter of 1998, Malaysian
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was the second consecutive quarter for Malaysia's economy
to record a negative growth in the past 10 years. In the first
quarter this year, Malaysia's gross domestic product (GDP)
declined by 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bank Negara Malaysia, the state bank, announced
Thursday afternoon that the GDP of the country in the second
quarter this year declined by 6.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's economy was badly affected by the regional financial
and economic crisis prompted by what was called speculative
attacks on the regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that the country's GDP declined to the level of
40 billion U.S. dollars compared to that of 100 billion dollars
before the onset of the economic crisis in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income also declined from 5,000 dollars to 2,000
dollars now, Mahathir said at a meet-the-people gathering in
Kuching, capital of Sarawak, East Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"Even though the rogue speculators only get between 5 billion
U.S. dollars and 10 billion U.S. dollars, we lost 60 billion U.S.
dollars just like that," he was quoted by the Malaysian national
news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia must make preparations from now to avoid
a catastrophe from which it would be most difficult to recover.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has worked out plans to revive the
economy and they have shown some results because the country has
not bowed to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) as expected by
the foreign media.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia would try to revive banks and companies which
could help reactivate the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's economy grew rapidly during the past decade with an
average growth rate of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the last quarter of 1997, Malaysia's economy expanded by 6.9
percent. 
</P>
