<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Coast Has Potential Diamond Reserves: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- There may be "rich reserves" of
diamonds in the coastal areas of Angola, an official with the
South African company De Bees disclosed at a seminar here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ian Corbett, head of the resources department of De Beers, the
largest diamond explorer in Africa, noted that these potential
diamonds have been washed down to the coastal areas by the many
rivers and deposited there.
</P>
<P>
Given that there are rich reserves of precious stones in the
hinterland of the southern African country, it is worthwhile
investing in the exploration of the potential reserves, said
Corbett.
</P>
<P>
He believed that greatest prospects are seen around the outlet
of Kwanza River in mid-northern coast.
</P>
<P>
Angola is one of the biggest diamond producers in Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics released by the Angolan Ministry
of Geology and Mines, in 1997 the state-run mining companies
produced 43,170,000 karats of precious stones worth 120 million
U.S. Dollars while the informal explorers dug out 88,200,000
karats worth 239 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Angola has its major mining areas in northeastern
provinces of Lunda-Noret and Lunda-Sul.
</P>
<P>
De Beers invested 50 million U.S. Dollars in the exploration
and production of various diamonds in Lunda-Noret in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke082767 -Philippine Gov't, MILF Rebels Sign Agreement of Intent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) Thursday signed an agreement
of intent as proof of their sincerity to pursue talks until a
peace accord is reached.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony, held in Simuay, Sultan Kudarat,
Maguindanao province in the southern Philippines, was signed by
government chief negotiator Orlando Soriano and his MILF
counterpart Aleem Abdulaziz Mimbantas.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the ceremony were Presidential Assistant for
Peace Process Manuel Yan, Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces
General Joselin Nazareno, MILF deputy chief for political affairs
Ghadzali and Libyan Ambassador to the Philippines Muhammad Al
Azzarouk.
</P>
<P>
In the agreement, the two parties said they will pursue the
peace negotiations as soon as possible and resolutely continue the
negotiations until a settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
They also affirmed their commitment to protecting and
respecting human rights in accordance with the principles set
forth in the Charter of the United Nations and the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to negotiate with sincerity to pacify
conflicts, and pledged to implement joint agreements previously
signed between them, such as the ceasefire agreement signed on
July 18, 1997 in Cagayan de Oro City and other supplement
agreements.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that there will be lasting peace in Mindanao
when there is mutual trust, justice, freedom, and tolerance for
the identity, culture, way of life and aspirations of all peoples
of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Government officials and MILF leaders lauded the agreement and
expressed hope for the continuation of the peace process in
Mindanao under the Joseph Estrada administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
