<HEADLINE> China's Museum on Primitive Religious Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- China's first museum of a
primitive religious rite used to exorcize evil spirits, or "Nuo",
opened to the public this morning in Tongren City of Guizhou
Province, southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,500 relics, masks, musical instruments used in "Nuo"
rites, and scripts of "Nuo" ballads are on display in the museum.
</P>
<P>
Tongren City has a great deal of "Nuo" culture and relics, as
well as more than 500 "Nuo" troupes with over 5,000 performers.
</P>
