<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Sets up Dengue Express Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government health
facilities have set up dengue fever express centers in some hot
spot areas to properly screen patients for early treatment and
management, the Department of Health said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The department has declared Manila, Caloocan City, Quezon City
and Valenzuela in Metro Manila and San Pablo City in Laguna, San
Antonio in Nueva Ecija and Quezon province as hot spots for dengue
fever.
</P>
<P>
It said dengue express lanes are strategically located in
health centers, hospitals and other government health facilities
for prompt diagnosis and screening of the danger signs in
patients.
</P>
<P>
Strict monitoring of dengue patients should be done, especially
when the fever subsides after three days, it said.
</P>
<P>
Dengue needs no extraordinary treatment and mild cases can be
treated at home. A patient usually recovers within three to five
days.
</P>
<P>
Death in dengue occurs, however, if treatment is delayed and
there is inappropriate administration of intravenous fluids, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, with dengue fever yet to peak from September to
October, the department records show that from January to July
this year, 7,754 dengue fever cases were reported nationwide, with
a 2-percent death rate.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 and 1997, the country recorded 14,648 and 12,811 dengue
fever cases respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
