<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Call for Serious Review of This Year's Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese lawmakers have viewed
the ongoing national combat against floods with mixed feelings,
and have called for a serious review of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
In examining a report of the State Council on flood-control
operations at the fourth meeting of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress here today, the lawmakers expressed
appreciation for the national endeavor, especially the Chinese
Communist Party's leadership and the army's contribution.
</P>
<P>
However, they also expressed concerns about the deteriorating
environment, which is believed to be the major cause for this
year's flooding.
</P>
<P>
Luo Di'an said the raging floods were caused by widespread
deforestation resulting in serious soil erosion and inadequate
water conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xuan said that flood-fighting is just like a battle which
tests officials at all levels. However, some officials who went to
the flood-stricken areas sought special comforts and asked to be
housed in air-conditioned rooms and eat soft-shelled turtles,
considered highly nutritious in Chinese cuisine.
</P>
<P>
"We should not tolerate such officials," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Yao Zhengyan, former vice minister of Water Resources, said the
flooding has sounded an alarm to the nation, and he worries that
more serious floods could hit China in the future unless the
central government increases investment to build modern water
conservancy projects and step up efforts to protect the
environment.
</P>
<P>
His ideas were echoed by An Zhendong, vice chairman of the
Standing Committee of the Heilongjiang Provincial People's
Congress. An pointed out that the root cause of the flooding on
the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers in northeast China is excessive
tree cutting in the upper reaches of the two rivers.
</P>
<P>
According to An, the Lesser Xinggan Mountains on the upper
reaches of the Nenjiang River is now treeless and the Greater
Xinggan Mountains is facing the same fate.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Chunyun, vice chairman of the NPC Standing Committee,
said the central government will shut down timber factories along
the upper reaches of the Yangtze River to ban the indiscriminate
felling of trees there.
</P>
<P>
The same measure will also be adopted in northeast China,
Jiang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Games Countdown to be Staged in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Amateur Sports Federation
and Olympic Committee of Hong Kong will organize a 13th Asian
Games Countdown at the end of the month to mark the grand sports
event to be held in Thailand in December.
</P>
<P>
T.T. Fok, president of the Amateur Sports Federation and
Olympic Committee of Hong Kong, said at a press conference
Thursday that Hong Kong is to make a strong showing because Hong
Kong must demonstrate solidarity with the rest of Asia in these
challenging times and exude confidence in themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Games are not a diversion, but a celebration of the
continent's shared identity and a manifestation of Asia's hope in
the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Games are a chance for the athletes to come together and
hone their talents in the prelude to the Olympic Games in 2000,
Fok said.
</P>
<P>
The Countdown ceremony will be held at Time Square, Causeway
Bay, in downtown Hong Kong on August 30. 
</P>
