<HEADLINE> Southern African States to Hold Summit In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) will hold its summit in Mauritius
from September 13 to 14, according to a report reaching here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
SADC Secretary-General Kaire Mbuende said in Zimbabwean
capital Harare Tuesday that the summit will review the political
situation in the southern African region. In Angola, one of the
SADC's 14 member states, the faltering peace process has been
stranded because of the violent operations by the opposition
movement Nation Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Mbuende noted that the unfolding conflicts in the Democratic
Republic of Congo will also be addressed at the summit.
</P>
<P>
There has been positive economic growth in the region though
it is not as good as that of last year, said the SADC
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Mauritian summit will also discuss about the
food situation in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
As shown in the latest SADC food security bulletin available
here, the community now has some 1.2 million tons of maize
surplus largely from huge carry-over stocks in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
It said that the region has an overall cereal deficit of
510,000 tons, a shortfall of 1,35 million tons of wheat, 107,000
tons of rice and 2.42 million tons of millet.
</P>
<P>
The community was putting together protocols which include
tourism and the setting up of a tribunal to solve internal
differences.
</P>
<P>
The protocols on energy, transport, communications and
education had been ratified by member states, Mbuende said.
</P>
<P>
Botswana, Tanzania, Mauritius and Zimbabwe had indicated they
would ratify the protocol on trade, he said, adding that there
was a 24 percent increase in intra-regional trade.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the draft declarations on refugees and free movement
of people within SADC and another one on anti-corruption will
also be considered at the coming summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Subcommission Calls for Lifting of Embargo on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Subcommission
on the Prevention of Discrimination and the Protection of
Minorities has approved a resolution calling on the international
community and the U.N. Security Council to lift economic sanctions
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In the resolution adopted here Wednesday afternoon, the
subcommission of the UN Commission on Human Rights cited
"unacceptable" declines in the levels of health, nutrition, health
care, employment and agriculture, and a rise in infant mortality.
</P>
<P>
The resolution titled "The Humanitarian Situation in Iraq" said
an embargo that condemned an innocent people to hunger, disease,
ignorance and even death without attaining the objectives for
which it was declared was a flagrant violation of economic, social
and cultural rights and of international law.
</P>
<P>
The Subcommission on the Prevention of Discrimination and the
Protection of Minorities, the Commission on Human Rights'
principal body of experts, began its fiftieth session at the
Palais des Nations in Geneva on August 3 and will end on August 28.
</P>
<P>
Created by the Commission on Human Rights in 1947, the
subcommission is made up of 26 independent experts representing
countries from the five regional groups. According to their
mandate, the experts undertake studies and make recommendations to
the Commission on Human Rights concerning the prevention of
discrimination, the protection of the rights of minorities and the
protection of human rights and fundamental freedoms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
