<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Collectors Fancy Food Coupons (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 26 (Xinhua)-- Abolished food coupons, which
used to be called "the lubricating oil of the currency" by Chinese
economists, have set off a new trend in the Chinese collection
market.
</P>
<P>
In a collectors center in Hangzhou, the capital of east China's
Zhejiang Province, food coupons of various designs are carefully
classified and displayed, and sellers and collectors bargain for
the colorful certificates.
</P>
<P>
Food coupons were used for about forty years in China until
their withdrawal from the country's grain circulation system in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
For decades, each Chinese urban resident was allocated food
coupons with a fixed monthly quota of 13 kilograms due to the food
shortage, and one could not buy foodstuffs in stores without them.
</P>
<P>
But all this is now a thing of the past. Today, food coupons are
becoming collectors' items for some people all over the country.
</P>
<P>
One Hangzhou coupon seller, Xie Liejun, aged 42, said that
food coupons issued in the early 1960s are the most valuable,
because many Chinese people couldn't get enough food to eat at
that time. In his stall display, one food coupon issued in 1960
with a face value of 0.5 kilograms was priced at 300 yuan
(about 36 U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Collectors Fancy Food Coupons (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yu Jiazheng, secretary-general of the Zhejiang Collection
Association, said that over the past forty years about 2,000
food-coupon in 10,000 editions were issued by the central
government and governments at the provincial and municipal levels.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Zhu Lianke, 74, a retired PLA officer in Hangzhou,
held an exhibition of his private collection of more than 10,000
food coupons issued by 30 provinces and autonomous regions at
different periods. His fascinating collection is the fruit of
searches made by him and his friends all over the country.
</P>
<P>
The food coupons issued during the Cultural Revolution
(1966-1976) are the Zhu's favorites, some of which are printed
with Mao Zedong's quotations and pictures of the Red Guards.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that one entrepreneur offered two million yuan (about
240,000 U.S. dollars) to buy his collection, but he
declined. Instead, he plans to open a coupon museum to display the
marked imprint of past times.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Hangzhou Food Bureau, who used to be in
charge of distributing these coupons, said the first coupon in
Hangzhou was issued in 1955, and that besides food coupons, there
were 22 other kinds needed by residents to buy necessities like
clothing, matches, salt, cigarettes, soaps, wine and pork.
</P>
<P>
Mao Zhaoxi, a history professor at Hangzhou University, said
that these abolished coupons are witnesses to China's development
since the economic reforms and opening up began in 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
