<HEADLINE> S. Africa Tightens Security for NAM Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- South African police and
the Foreign Ministry have vowed to be extra vigilant to secure
delegates from 112 countries at the forthcoming Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM) summit after Tuesday's bombing in a Cape Town
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
Overall security for the meeting, which opens in Durban
Saturday, will be thoroughly evaluated in the wake of the blast,
which claimed one life and left 27 injured, The Star reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A security service spokesperson said they were prepared for
all eventualities. He said "substantial" numbers of police and
security personnel had already been deployed.
</P>
<P>
Security had been stepped up in Durban after the bombing of
U.S. targets in Kenya and Tanzania on August 7.
</P>
<P>
The first delegates arrive at the VIP terminal adjoining
Durban's international airport Thursday. At least 80 kings,
presidents and prime ministers from all over the world are
expected.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an anti-crime protest by members of a provincial
agricultural union, which was planned to coincide with the
summit, has been canceled "in the national interest".  
</P>
