<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Finance Mohieddin Al Ghareeb
issued a decree Wednesday to exempt local components of the new
ventures from any customs for the year 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Fawzi, chairman of the General Authority for
Investment, said this would give impetus to new investment
projects governed by both the free trade zones and domestic
investment systems.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The USAID has agreed to extend a grant of some 800,000
Egyptian pounds (233,918 U.S. dollars) to the Egyptian Ministry of
Agriculture to implement a modern data system in agricultural
production, which is due to be completed in mid 2002.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom said that the project
aims at utilizing modern technological tools to automize the
building of expertise systems which would be applied in the
fields of plant and animal production.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian company for mobile phone services has
signed contracts worth of 400 million Egyptian pounds (170 million
dollars) to develop and expand the mobile phone system, and to
equip it with latest technologies to provide the subscribers with
the best service.
</P>
<P>
The Alam Al Yom reported that the American Motorola company
will undertake the delivery of amplifying stations as well as
modern communications for mobile phones so as to extend the
service to numerous towns and tourist centers in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The World Bank has pledged to support Yemen to
fullfil its economic, financial and administrative reform programs.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Middle East and North Africa Department of the
World Bank Ander Sud said the Bank had decided to allocate an
additional 50 million dollars for social welfare projects in
Yemen. He anticipated that a similar sum will donated by donor
countries.
</P>
<P>
Sud said that ever since the economic reform program was
launched in 1995, the World Bank had provided about 360 million
dollars to Yemen to carry out 10 projects.
</P>
<P>
ALGERS -- The Algerian Ministry of Labor, Social Protection and
Vocational Training announced Wednesday that the minimum monthly
wage would increase from 5,400 Algerian dinars (93 dollars) to
6000 (103 dollars) as from September 1.
</P>
<P>
According to the Algerian news agency, wages of assistants
employed in public authorities and departments will be increased
by 5 percent from September 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
