<HEADLINE> HK External trade Registers Sharper Decrease in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's
re-exports, domestic exports and imports in July this year all
registered sharper year-on-year decreases than in the preceding
months.
</P>
<P>
This is revealed in the external trade figures for July
released Thursday by the Census and Statistics Department of Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The value of total exports (comprising re-exports and domestic
exports) decreased by 13 percent in July 1998 over a year earlier
to 119.1 billion HK dollars (15.3 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the value of re-exports decreased by 13
percent to 100.9 billion HK dollars (12.9 billion U.S. dollars),
while that of domestic exports fell by 10 percent to 18.2
billion HK dollars (2.3 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of imports decreased even more substantially in July,
by 18 percent over a year earlier to 123.1 billion HK dollars
(15.8 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A visible trade deficit of 4.0 billion HK dollars (0.51 billion
U.S. dollars), equivalent to 3.3 percent of the value of imports,
was recorded in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
On these latest trade figures, a Government Secretariat
spokesman noted that the marked decline in exports was due in
part to the disruption in air cargo handling services at the new
airport during the month.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the spokesman said, the serious flooding in
Central China could have disrupted Hong Kong's exports by rail to
the Chinese mainland. Apart from the influence of these disruption
factors, the setback in exports in July also occurred as a
continuation of the weak export performance caused by the plunge
in import demand from Japan, South Korea and the ASEAN economies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
