<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drive Responsible For Bus Accident Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The driver responsible for the
bus accident that killed seven people, including six from Taiwan,
in Gansu Province last Saturday has been arrested, according to
local sources.
</P>
<P>
Wei Guiguo was found to be the driver of the truck which
crossed the median strip and collided head-on with a tour bus
carrying 17 people, 14 of them tourists from Taiwan, on August
22. The tour bus driver and five Taiwan tourists were killed
instantly and another Taiwan resident died later.
</P>
<P>
The high speed of the two vehicles is believed to have been a
factor, sources said, adding that it will take at least 40 days
before a verdict is decided.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the local police returned the belongings
recovered at the accident scene to the victims' relatives who
expressed appreciation for the efforts the government has made in
handling the accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Bodies Spotted at Plane Crash Site in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Rescuers spotted the bodies of
two females as they approached the crash site of a passenger plane
in mountains in western Nepal, an officer said.
</P>
<P>
"It is very confirmed," said Surash Acharya, who is in charge
of information dissemination at the Rescue and Coordination Center
at the capital's Tribhuvan International Airport.
</P>
<P>
He said no other bodies could be seen, adding that the rescue
team saw the bodies 15 meters away from the crash site at an
altitude of 12,000 feet (some 4,000 meters) about 13 kilometers
southwest of Mt. Annapurna I.
</P>
<P>
He said the path towards the crash site is very tough and
steep, and the rescue team had returned to its base camp, about
700 meters away from the crash site, for food.
</P>
<P>
The police were trying to reach the crash site with the help of
helicopter and rope, but it was getting more and more foggy there,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Twin Otter aircraft lost contact five minutes after taking
off last Friday in Jomsom, western Nepal. It was found crashed
into pieces Tuesday morning at the crash site. Those 18 on board
include three crew members and three Indians.
</P>
<P>
Rain and thick fog hampered the rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
Armymen managed Wednesday to build a helipad near the crash
site and 12 persons were dropped there, the local radio and
television reported.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated aircraft was leased by the private-owned Lumbini
Airways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
