<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't Denies Rift Between Defense Chief, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
Thursday denied there is a rift between Defense Secretary Orlando
Mercado and some military officers.
</P>
<P>
In his regular press briefing, Presidential Spokesman Jerry
Barican said that top military officers led by Armed Forces Chief
of Staff Joselin Nazareno have reiterated their allegiance to the
Constitution as well as to President Joseph Estrada and Mercado.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mercado, who is on a six-day official trip to
Indonesia, Brunei and Thailand, declared Thursday that he is ready
to quit his post if Estrada would side with some military
generals.
</P>
<P>
Mercado made the statement in an interview with Radio Station
DZXL to air his stance after the Association of Generals and Flag
Officers (AGFO), a group composed of retired generals, accused him
of publicly berating a ranking general before other ranking
officers.
</P>
<P>
The word war erupted when 650 retired generals reacted to the
alleged arrogance of Mercado and his statement that generals are
incompetent and corrupt as he ordered an investigation of the
military-run financial institution, the Retirement Service Benefit
System, of reported irregularities.
</P>
<P>
Catalino Villanueva, AGFO president, said in a statement that
many of the generals are competent. He asked Mercado to stop
making sweeping accusation "that generals are incompetent and
corrupt."
</P>
<P>
In the interview, Mercado said that if the president has no
more confidence in him, he is ready to quit.
</P>
<P>
Barican stressed that Mercado has the president's full support,
trust and confidence.
</P>
<P>
He said that aside from reaffirming their unswerving loyalty to
the president and Mercado, the military top brass also supported
the president's order for an investigation of fund anomalies in
the Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Estrada has said that the Department of National
Defense should push through with such an investigation in line
with his administration's campaign against graft and corruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
