<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: South Africa Vows to Hunt down Bombers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The South African
authorities have vowed to hunt down the bombers behind Tuesday's
deadly blast in a Cape Town restaurant, which is possibly "the
first incident of international terror" on South African soil.
</P>
<P>
"The government is of firm resolve that whoever perpetrated
this deed of utter callousness must be assured that we will hunt
them down until justice takes its full course," said a statement
issued Wednesday after a special meeting of all ministers.
</P>
<P>
One man was killed and 27 other people, including
international tourists and children, were injured in Tuesday
night's blast in the U.S.-franchised Planet Hollywood restaurant,
which is located at the heart of a busy leisure complex in Cape
Town.
</P>
<P>
The bombing is suspected to be linked to recent U.S. missile
strikes against the alleged Muslim terrorist bases in Sudan and
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The blast has drawn condemnation from around the globe,
including from U.S. President Bill Clinton and South African
President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The statement said: "No one should and will be allowed to use
South African soil to play out their fantasies, whatever their
vile motivation."
</P>
<P>
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi, while inspecting
the scene, reaffirmed that South Africa refused to become the
theater of acts of international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi, fully backed by Justice Minister Dullah Omar, said
there were "firm leads" in the investigation into the case and
arrests were expected soon. But the security minister declined
to give further details.
</P>
<P>
Video footage taken by surveillance cameras mounted behind the
bombed restaurant bar may provide an early breakthrough for
detectives working around the clock to probe the case.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the suspect apparently has links with a
local extremist grouping.
</P>
<P>
Police said that a home-made device, probably a pipe bomb or
variation of such one, caused the explosion. It was not known
how the bomb was detonated.
</P>
<P>
Police have offered a 250,000-Rand (40,000 U.S. Dollars)
reward for information leading to the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a team of the U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation
(FBI) agents, who had been actively involved in investigating the
bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania earlier this
month, have arrived in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
South African police are also looking into possible links
between the restaurant bombing and other blasts in recent months
on the Cape Flats, arguably the most volatile area in the
country.
</P>
<P>
President Mandela expressed his confidence in early arrests
following a detailed briefing by National Police Commissioner
George Fivaz.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said that the police are hot on the heels of the
perpetrators. "They (the police) have an idea of who committed
the crime. I am confident they will be arrested soon," he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly was due to hold a special debate on the
bombing Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
