<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Condemns Tel Aviv Bombing Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu Thursday strongly condemned the bombing attack
in Tel Aviv, which injured a dozen people.
</P>
<P>
"This attack is another sign that we need to fight terror,"
said Netanyahu in his Jerusalem office before meeting former
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said the latest attack showed the terrorists were
acting against Israeli civilians not only in the West Bank city
of Hebron but anywhere.
</P>
<P>
A total of 12 people were injured Thursday morning when a bomb
put inside a garbage can exploded at an intersection of the
bustling Allenby Street and Rothschild Boulevard. A pregnant woman
and two children were among the injured, one of which is in
serious condition.
</P>
<P>
The others suffered from minor burns to only shock. Tel Aviv
police sealed off the area to conduct investigation immediately
after the blast. They found that the bomb, weighing about one to
two pounds, was packed with nails.
</P>
<P>
No one has claimed responsibility for the bombing, but the
police suspected it to be a terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
Tel Aviv has been a frequent target for Palestinian militants,
led by the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), who have been
launching a terror campaign through bombing buses and public
places in order to wreck the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces have been put on high alert in the past
days following the U.S. missile attacks against suspected Islamic
terrorist bases in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Anti-U.S. Islamic activists have warned to launch retaliatory
attacks against American and Israeli targets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ahmed Tibi, senior advisor to Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat, also condemned the Tel
Aviv bombing after his meeting with Arafat in the West Bank city
of Ramallah Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the bombing should be condemned no matter who
carried it out, because it was aimed at innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli Cabinet Secretary Denny Naveh said this
condemnation was far from enough. He demanded the PNA publicly
condemns all the terror attacks against settlers.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a Jewish settler was stabbed to death by a
Palestinian in Hebron. Israel has complained that Arafat did not
issue condemnation of it.
</P>
<P>
The latest attack is expected to help Israel increase its
pressure on the PNA to crack down tougher on militants. David Bar
Illan, Netanyahu's media adviser, said Thursday that the peace
process cannot continue unless Israeli security is secured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
