<HEADLINE> Disarmament Conference Discusses Landmine Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Agreement should be possible
within the Conference on Disarmament to negotiate a ban on
transfers of anti-personnel landmines, a special coordinator on
anti-personnel landmine of the conference said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As a result of consultations among regional group coordinators,
three of the regional groups -- China, the Eastern Group and the
Western Group -- had reached a consensus on supporting the
proposals made by special coordinator John B. Campbell, who is
also Australia's disarmament ambassador.
</P>
<P>
Campbell said that one group, the Group of 21, still required
further time to consider his proposals. But "I have been advised
of a large measure of support" even within the group where
discussions are continuing, he added.
</P>
<P>
"I remain confident that with some further work in the year
ahead, we shall be able to reach a resolution of the issue and
undertake the work which I believe the majority of members wish
the conference to undertake," Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that a consensus necessary for the
conference to take an early decision to establish an ad hoc
committee would be achieved next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
