<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Will Retire from Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar said he will retire from the military after
handing over to an elected civilian government in May next year.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement Wednesday in Pretoria before ending his
three-day official visit to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"I have put in at least 35 years in the military and whether I
was going to become the president or not (taking over from late
leader General Sani Abacha), I was going to retire quietly to my
village and that is what I intend to do," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian leader asked journalists to judge the sincerity
of his government to hand over power to a civilian administration
by its deeds and not just by its promises.
</P>
<P>
"We have released political prisoners, we have dropped some
charges, and we have set up an independent electoral commission,
which has already been put in place, and have also released the
transition program," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the relations between Nigeria and South Africa, Abubakar
said the problem that made it frosty had been ironed out during
his discussions with President Nelson Mandela and other senior
South African officials in the past few days. 
</P>
