<HEADLINE> Sub-Contract For Australian Military Communications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States' company
Boeing in Australia Thursday signed the first major sub-contract
for a project designed to provide a common communications network
for the Australian Defense Force (ADF) by 2002, linking command
centers with deployed aircraft, ships and land forces.
</P>
<P>
The contract with Thiess Contractors Pty Ltd, worth about 16
million U.S. dollars, is for construction work involved in the
High Frequency Modernization Project.
</P>
<P>
"Thiess will carry out the construction work or modification to
buildings and the civil infrastructure required in support of the
Modernized High Frequency Communications System," said Project
General Manager Tony Swansson after the signing ceremony in
Brisbane, capital city of the state of Queensland, Australia.
</P>
<P>
The project was designed to provide a common network for the
ADF, Australia's armed forces, with telephone-like simplicity.
</P>
<P>
The new system will involve the establishment of transmitter
and receiver stations at North West Cape in the state of Western
Australia, near Darwin city in the Northern Territory, in the
Riverina region of the state of New South Wales and Townsville in
Queensland.
</P>
<P>
Boeing engineers expect to finalize the building and civil
works design of the system during this year and early 1999, with
construction due to be completed during 2000.
</P>
<P>
The ADF force will begin using the system in 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
