<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's GDP Down 6.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's gross domestic
product (GDP) fell by 6.6 percent in real terms in the second
quarter of this year, the Bank of Korea said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The GDP fall followed a 3.9-percent contraction registered in
the first quarter, pushing the country's economy into a deeper
recession.
</P>
<P>
The second-quarter contraction was the biggest quarterly drop
since the fourth quarter of 1980 when South Korea suffered a
second "oil shock" and registered a minus 7.8 percent in GDP.
</P>
<P>
Record declines in consumption and investment, coupled with
slower export growth, are blamed for the GDP plunge, said the
central bank.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predicted that the South Korean economy is expected to
suffer another sharp contraction in the second half of the year
since there are no signs of improvement in consumption, investment
and export.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the South Korean government predicted a 4 percent GDP
contraction for this year. But senior officials, including
Minister of Finance and Economy Lee Kyu-sung, said that a
contraction of five-six percent was almost inevitable.
</P>
<P>
Some economists here are even more pessimistic, forecasting a
seven-percent contraction in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
