<HEADLINE> Bulgarian President Leaves for Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian President Petar Stoyanov
on Thursday left here for Moscow to begin a three-day visit which
he hopes will help lay a new foundation for the Bulgarian-Russian
relations.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov had said that his Russia trip was aimed at "getting
rid of old prejudice" and laying a new foundation for the future
development of the relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The visit, originally scheduled for December 1997 but twice
postponed because of Russian President Boris Yeltsin's health
problem and the natural gas row between the two countries, came
after the ruling and opposition parties reached a wide-ranging
consensus on how to deal with the relations with Russia.
</P>
<P>
On August 24-25, Stoyanov held comprehensive and detailed
consultations with Prime Minister Ivan Kostov, former President
Zheliu Zhelev and opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
After these discussions, Stoyanov said that he and the
government had found a common and responsible position on the
Bulgaria-Russia relations.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov said that Bulgaria's bid to join the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization and the European Union is not directed at
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia was the largest trade partner of Bulgaria in 1997. It is
also crucial for Bulgaria to have Russia's support in its bid to
become the Balkan energy distribution center.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria wants Russia to supply crude oil and natural gas and
take part in laying international pipelines that will run through
Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Bulgaria and Russia will discuss this
issue during Stoyanov's Russia tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
