<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Crashes to Post-Float Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar crashed
to a post-float low against the U.S. currency Thursday morning,
shedding one U.S. cent in value on overnight foreign exchange
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Australian currency opened local trade at 56.45 U.S. cents
after reaching an overnight nadir of 56.25 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Thursday morning it fell further to 56.10 U.S. cents, its
lowest level since being floated in December 1983.
</P>
<P>
The previous low was 57.10 U.S. cents, reached on July 28,
1986.
</P>
<P>
Federal Treasurer Peter Costello put the sliding Australian
dollar down to international developments.
</P>
<P>
"It is international developments that people have taken into
account," Costello told reporters here when asked why the dollar
was falling.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was also substantially weaker against the
Japanese yen Thursday morning, losing 1.5 yen overnight to 81.42
from 82.90 late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
And the local unit was also trading at 1.0214 German marks from
1.0312 previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
