<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down on Yen Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A combination of a weak local
currency, falls in overseas markets and futures selling drove the
Australian sharemarket lower Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index slumped 47.4 points, or 1.82
percent, to 2560.6, off a low of 2553.7.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed in local trade at 56.43.
</P>
<P>
Intersuisse equities manager Andrew Sekely said that the
combination of the weaker Australian dollar, declines in overseas
bourses, particularly in Tokyo and New York, and the futures
contract at a discount forced the local market down.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed down 26.8 points, or 2.72
percent, at 958.0 and the all industrials index closed down 74.7
points, or 1.62 percent, at 4538.4.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 285.66 million valued at 1.059 billion
Australian dollars (598.33 million U.S. dollars), with falls
easily outweighing rises 816 to 344 respectively and 406 stocks
were steady.
</P>
<P>
Topping volume was Telstra Corp with a turnover of 16.138
million shares, with its instalment receipts losing five cents, or
1.12 percent.
</P>
<P>
BHP led the market lower, plunging 53.9 cents, or 4.03 percent,
as weaker commodity prices and concerns over less Japanese demand
for exports spooked investors, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
Other resource stocks also lost ground, with WMC falling 12 and
Rio Tinto dropping 29.4.
</P>
<P>
ANZ Banking Group, which has significant overseas operations
and has had trouble in the volatile Russian market, was the big
loser among the banks, plunging 42, or 4.29 percent, National
Australia Bank fell 37.5, Westpac Banking Corp fell 16 and
Commonwealth Bank of Australia fell 20.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed down 17.2 points, or 1.85 percent, while
gold bullion closed at 281.15 U.S. dollars from 282.45 Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
