<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts Insurance Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Participants at an insurance
seminar held here today urged the insurance industry to draw
lessons from the Asia financial crisis and work out
countermeasures to offset the negative impact of the crisis on
China's insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 experts and scholars from the Chinese mainland
and Taiwan are participating in the seminar, sponsored
by the China Insurance Society.
</P>
<P>
The participants discussed such topics as the development of
the insurance industry in the mainland and Taiwan, the impact of
the Asian financial crisis on the insurance industry and possible
countermeasures, motor vehicle insurance, life insurance, capital
management and insurance supervision.
</P>
<P>
The speakers generally agreed that, although the Asian
crisis did not have a direct impact on the insurance industry of
the mainland and Taiwan, the indirect negative impact should not
be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
Wu Min from the Reinsurance Company of the People's Insurance
Company of China said that to offset the negative consequences of
the financial crisis, China's insurance industry should give full
support to the government's economic reforms and restructure
business operations in accordance with the law of economic
development.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that supervision of the insurance industry should
be reinforced, and related laws and regulations be further
improved so that China's insurance market can develop in a healthy
fashion.
</P>
<P>
Hu Xinmin, managing deputy manager of Hua An Property Insurance
Co. Ltd., said that China's insurance industry should pay close
attention to the Asian financial crisis and adopt effective measures
as early as possible to avoid risks.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that stricter supervision should be made over the
development of life insurance products; capital management should
be regulated to prevent non-performing assets; a scientific
supervision index system should be established to focus on payment
ability; and insurance companies' internal control should be
improved.
</P>
<P>
According to World Bank estimates, by the year 2000 insurance
premiums in the Chinese mainland will total some 200 billion
yuan, while at present it is only about 100 billion yuan,
indicating great potential for the Chinese insurance market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
