<HEADLINE> Afghan Northern Warlord Seeking Turkish Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Afghan northern warlord Abdul
Rashid Dostum is seeking support from Turkey in order to form a
front against the Taliban militia, local newspaper Turkiye
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dostum, a former general of the Uzbek militia, arrived here two
days ago for a visit. He told Turkiye in an exclusive interview
that he hoped that Turkey would exert efforts to contain the
Taliban militia in Afghanistan, which has contolled most of the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Dostum held talks on Wednesday with high-ranking officials of
the General Staff of the Turkish Armed Forces, the Foreign
Ministry and the Organization of the National Intelligence on the
latest developments in Afghanistan, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has urged the Pakistan, Taliban's strong supporter, to
prevent the Taliban militia from harming the civilians and
innocent people in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated that permanent peace could only be established
in Afghanistan through peaceful means and negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Dostum told the paper that he did not escape from Afghanistan
and would stay in Turkey for another two days before returning to
his country for the fighting to "liberate Afghanistan".
</P>
<P>
He said that new attacks would be launched against the Taliban
forces, which have recently conquered Mazari Sharif, a major
northern stronghold for the Northern Alliance led by the ousted
President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Dostum turned to support Rabbani after the Taliban forces drove
his government out of the capital Kabul in September 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
