<HEADLINE> Cambodian Ruling Party Asks Opposition to Stop Hostilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Cambodian People's
Party (CPP) Thursday called on all political parties to stop
hostilities and expressed its determination to resolutely oppose
any attempt to form an interim government.
</P>
<P>
The CPP, led by Second Prime Minister Hun Sen, made a
three-point statement Thursday accusing some party leaders of
making provocative speeches on the CPP and its leaders.
</P>
<P>
It asked the opposition parties led by Sam Rainsy and Prince
Norodom Ranariddh to stop illegal demonstrations and other
activities against the CPP, saying that they do not serve the
interests of the country, people and political parties.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the CPP made an official public response
to opposition's sit-in demonstrations beginning from Monday and to
Ranariddh's call for the formation of an interim government led by
King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the CPP believes that any attempt to form an
interim government will violate the country's Constitution and
sabotage the spirit of the Paris peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
"It is especially against the will of the Cambodian people and
the results of the July 26 elections which were held freely and
fairly under the observation of the international community," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement called on those parties who had won the seats in
the new parliament to respect country's laws and the will of the
voters to maintain the order of the society.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the CPP said it plans to hold a meeting with
Funcinpec party at any time to resolve the problems the country
now faces with.
</P>
<P>
The two major opposition political parties had rejected the
election results and vowed to block the formation of a new
government until their complaints are satisfied. Ranariddh and Sam
Rainsy even demanded Hun Sen to step down, saying they will not
join the government led by him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
