<HEADLINE> China, Japan to Further Environmental Protection Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Japanese government
officials, experts, scholars and entrepreneurs have expressed their
desire to further enhance bilateral cooperation in environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
They made this clear earlier today at a Sino-Japanese
environmental protection forum jointly sponsored by the China
Council for the Promotion of International Trade and the
Japan-China Association on Economy and Trade.
</P>
<P>
During the forum, about 200 representatives from the two
countries discussed issues such as environmental protection
policies and their mutual experience and bilateral cooperation in
this field.
</P>
<P>
Qu Geping, chairman of the Environment and Resources Protection
Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress, said that
China has a positive attitude toward international and regional
cooperation for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
With the support and joint efforts of the governments and
peoples of the two countries, he said, China and Japan have
enjoyed good cooperative relations in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral cooperation at various levels for environmental
policies, technologies and industries has exerted an important
influence in upgrading China's technologies, effectively
implementing the country's plans, and improving the environment of
China and the Asian-Pacific region, noted Qu.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Sino-Japanese exchanges and cooperation in
environmental protection is not only conducive to the
consolidation and development of bilateral economic and trade
relations, but also conducive to global cooperation on the
environment and the settlement of related problems.
</P>
<P>
There is great potential for bilateral exchanges and
cooperation in this field, Qu said, adding he hopes that China and
Japan can continue efforts for furthering bilateral cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
