<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Plunging in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued tumbling in
Tokyo Thursday with the key Nikkei index temporarily dropping to
its lowest level in three years.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 452.24 points, or 3.04
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 14,413.79, a closing low
for the year.
</P>
<P>
The index temporarily fell as low as 14,378.67, its lowest
level since July 3, 1995 when it marked 14,295.90.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, also slumped to a new closing low for the
year, ending at 1,116.97, down 30.24 points or 2.64 percent.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section rose to an estimated 500 million
shares from Wednesday's 412.26 million Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
All 19 major banks fell for the second straight trading day,
while several major export-oriented companies such as Hitachi,
Toyota Motor and Sharp dropped to new lows for the year due to
increasing worry of a worldwide price deflation.
</P>
<P>
With Japan's political parties deadlocked over a set of bills
aimed at reviving the banking system, investors had little reason
to hold onto banking shares, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,333 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outnumbered gainers 1,030 to 144, with 114 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
