<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Internet Economy to Nearly Quadruple in Four Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELSE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Internet economy of the
United States will grow to 518 billion U.S. dollars in 2002, the
research firm International Data Corporation (IDC) forecast this
week.
</P>
<P>
IDC defines the Internet economy, which will come to 124
billion dollars in 1998, as the combination of spending to build
Web businesses and applications and the revenue from products and
services sold over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
While technology deployment is the lion's share of the economy,
IDC said, significant spending is also occurring in marketing and
branding activities, professional services, content creation and
education and training.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers of hard goods are leading the spending in 1998,
with an estimated 23 billion dollars being invested by the
industry segment in Web applications for extranet, intranets and
commerce Web sites. Next among the top five industries are
communications/media and banking, each with 15 billion dollars to
be spent this year.
</P>
<P>
IDC said that it will announce its findings for the size and
future growth of the worldwide Internet economy at an Internet
executive forum to be held in September in San Jose, California.
</P>
<P>
The conference will examine the business models driving the
Internet economy and the barriers that must be overcome to fulfill
its potential.
</P>
<P>
IDC's research on the Internet economy is based on an analysis
of information technology (IT) budgets across major industries, as
well as non-IT budget technology spending. In addition, IDC
conducted a survey of 600 architects of the Internet economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
