<HEADLINE> 7 Killed in Landslides in Northeastern Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Three landslides triggered by
heavy rains Thursday killed seven people and left five missing in
two prefectures in northeastern Japan, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
In the village of Nishigo, Fukushima Prefecture, five people
died and one person was injured when a landslide hit a welfare
facility, while a separate landslide buried a private house in
another part of the village, killing one and leaving another
missing.
</P>
<P>
In the village of Taishin in the same prefecture, a 12-year-old
boy was killed when a landslide struck his house.
</P>
<P>
In Nasu, a summer resort in nearby Tochigi Prefecture, four
people went missing after ten houses were washed away by a
flooding river.
</P>
<P>
Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka told a news conference
that the Japanese government would take measures to prevent
further damage.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rains were triggered by the season's fourth typhoon
in waters off the Ogasawara Islands in the Pacific, about 1,000
kilometers south of Tokyo, the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
