<HEADLINE> New Zealand Dollar Hits 12-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand dollar hit a
12-year low Thursday as shock waves from the plunging Russian
ruble rocked financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The TV New Zealand reported this evening that the New Zealand
dollar fell to 48.11 cents of the U.S. dollar in Thursday's early
trading before bouncing back to 48.59 cents of the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The NZ dollar sell-off was bad news for the Reserve Bank, the
central bank of the country, which on Wednesday warned markets
that interest rates and the NZ dollar had fallen "too much". Local
financial markets responded by pushing the monetary conditions
index from negative 100 to negative 80.
</P>
<P>
The index measures the NZ dollar and interest rates. However,
the index of negative 80 was still outside the bank's desired
level, set a week ago of zero with a 50 point comfort zone either
side.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale interest rates rose Thursday to compensate for the
fall of the NZ dollar, with 90-day bank bills at 6.7 percent from
6.3 percent late last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
