<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project May Have Saved Flood Victims, Experts Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Three Gorges Dam Project
would have greatly ameliorated the damage done by the current
Yangtze River flooding at the mid and lower reaches of the river
if it were now in operation, according to experts quoted today in
the Beijing Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
The project, located near Yichang in central China's Hubei
Province, is a key state project for harnessing the Yangtze River
in a comprehensive way. With the cost of construction estimated at
50.09 billion yuan (6.05 billion U.S. dollars), the dam will have
many functions including flood control, power generation and the
facilitation of shipping on the river.
</P>
<P>
In July, the dam saw 12.16 billion cubic meters of water
flowing from the upper reaches, the largest amount in 121 years,
with an average flow rate of 45,400 cubic meters per second. Most
of the floodwater also came from the upper reaches in August.
</P>
<P>
This makes prominent the project's intended role in storing
water, which can prevent and control the crest from the upper
reaches from converging with those at the middle reaches, and
thereby protect 15 million people and 1.53 million hectares of
arable land in the lower reaches, according to experts with the
State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The massive reservoir will have a storage capacity of 22.15
billion cubic meters of water, four times that of the storage
capacity of the Jingjiang Flood Diversion Area.
</P>
<P>
"The operation of the reservoir will make the water diversion
project in the Jingjiang section almost unnecessary," said one
expert.
</P>
<P>
At the Jingjiang section of the Yangtze River, floods should
be diverted when the water flow rates reach 60,000 cubic meters
per second. And the situation becomes precarious when the flow
rate rises above 80,000 cubic meter per second.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Dam Project, scheduled for completion in the
year 2009, has a designed capacity to handle water flows rates as
high as 122,000 cubic meters per second, greatly enhancing its
flood-fighting capability.
</P>
<P>
The dam will be able to reduce the water flow rate from 87,100
cubic meter per second to 56,700 cubic meter per second, enabling
the water to go downstreams safely without the need for resorting
to diversions, the experts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing-Hong Kong Economic Cooperation Fair Scheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A fair promoting economic
cooperation between Beijing and Hong Kong with the theme "mutual
advantages for prosperity" will be held at the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center from October 12-14.
</P>
<P>
Yi Xiqun, chairman of the Beijing Foreign Trade and Economic
Commission, said that the fair will also include a symposium and a
photo exhibition about cooperation projects between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
Participants will discuss cooperation in the fields of
high-tech industries, the service trade and enterprise reform, Yi
said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Beijing will put forward over 500 projects
for overseas investors during the three-day event.
</P>
<P>
To date, Hong Kong-based businesses have established projects
of cooperation with 5,464 enterprises in Beijing, and investors
have put in a total of 10.72 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The fair will be jointly sponsored by the Beijing Foreign Trade
and Economic Commission, the Hong Kong Trade development Council,
and the Chinese General Chamber of Commerce of Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
