<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zoologists Discover "Twin Oocytes" in Giant Pandas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists working in
the Research Center for Giant Panda Breeding in Chengdu, capital
of southwest China's Sichuan Province, recently discovered "twin
oocytes" in the ovaries of two dead giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
Their discovery will provide new clues to explain why giant
pandas have such a high birth rate for twins.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Meijia, a zoologist at the center, said that first twin
oocytes were removed from the ovaries of a giant panda which died
of cirrhosis in August last year.
</P>
<P>
Researchers removed the eggs for external fertilization and
during the process found two small oocytes closely surrounded by
cumulus cells.
</P>
<P>
"The phenomenon, which we named "twin oocytes", has never been
reported in other animals", said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, researchers found another pair of "twin
oocytes" in a giant panda which died of senility. The discovery
led researchers to infer that "twin oocytes" commonly exist in the
ovaries of giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
The population of the endangered species currently stands at
around 1,000 pandas. While giant pandas are known to have a low
fertility,
</P>
<P>
statistics show that some 52 percent of giant pandas living in
captivity worldwide give birth to twins. However, extensive
experiments have determined the nonexistence of identical twins.
</P>
<P>
This has led some zoologists to conjecture that this has
resulted from repeated artificial fertilization which releases ova
at different times.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhang and his colleagues at the research base contend
the birth rate for giant panda twins is the result of "twin
oocytes".
</P>
<P>
"We plan to conduct further studies to determine how 'twin
oocytes' are formed and grow," said Zhang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Procrastination Adversely Impacts Cross-Straits Relations. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The most urgent task facing both
sides of the Taiwan Straits is to hold preparatory talks
concerning the timing, venue and topics for political
negotiations, according to one noted Chinese researcher.
</P>
<P>
However, he acknowledged that the procrastination and evasive
tactics adopted by the Taiwan side have adversely impacted
cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zaixi, a senior researcher with the China International
Strategic Studies, made the remarks in his signed article
published here today.
</P>
<P>
The 13th Session on National Reunification held in Taiwan in
late July ended with Taiwan authorities adopting a negative
attitude on the subject. They went so far as to table a proposal
for "ending hostilities by signing a cross-Straits peace agreement
based on the separate jurisdiction of parties on either side of
the Taiwan Straits", said Wang. He added the situation has thus
been the subject of great concern.
</P>
<P>
On May 20, 1996, the Taiwan authorities expressed their desire
to open negotiations free of any preconditions, and thereafter
reiterated the proposal on several occassions. Now, however, they
insist that the Chinese mainland recognize separate jurisdiction
prior to opening negotiations. "Does this represent a complete
reversal in previous position Taiwan authorities held concerning
negotiations?" questioned Wang.
</P>
<P>
If the Taiwan side sincerely adheres to the "reunification
goal" then there is no reason to oppose the mainland proposal for
"opening negotiations under the one China principle", according to
Wang. He added that it would be meaningless to hold negotiations
without adhering to the one China principle and China's
reunification goal.
</P>
<P>
The most recent poll conducted by the Taiwan authorities
indicate that some 52 percent of the common people in the island
province approve of opening negotiations across the straits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
