<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Needs 1.673 Bln Dollars to Stimulate Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will raise funds
to inject an additional 7.03 billion ringgit (about 1.673 billion
U.S. dollars) in order to stimulate the economy, Special Functions
Minister Tun Daim Zainuddin said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This additional allocation will be used to increase the demand
for goods and services, and implement projects to increase the
country's competitiveness while instituting a social safety net
for vulnerable groups in the society, he said in his keynote
address at the Round Table Discussion on the National Economic
Recovery Plan organized by the Oxford and Cambridge Society.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government will not hesitate to borrow from
abroad to finance its recovery plan, Daim said.
</P>
<P>
"The banking sector too has to contribute by shaking off its
over cautiousness towards lending, which if continued will further
choke the economy to death," he said, adding "by all means, be
prudent, but do not deny credit to profitable ventures. It is good
to remember that if all activities come to a halt, the banks
themselves will grind to a halt."
</P>
<P>
Daim said that Malaysia always welcomes foreign investment but
it is concerned about speculative "hot money" which creates
instability.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government is still open to productive ideas on
what else needs to be done to strengthen the financial and
corporate sectors or the capital market, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "it might also be timely for Malaysia to explore new
avenues, other than banks and the stock market, to source the
capital, and to meet our investment requirements."
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, the government is committed towards the
further development of the private debt securities market," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that contrary to prescriptions suggested by the
International Monetary Fund, an easier monetary policy and fiscal
expansion will be Malaysia's strategy to avert any possibility of
a depression.
</P>
<P>
"We at this stage should be concerned about deflation rather
than inflation since a deflationary situation will put further
pressure on our banking system and erode the efforts taken so far
to strengthen the economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Daim admitted that there was a crisis of confidence in the
country and that the private sector had lost total confidence.
</P>
<P>
He urged the private sector to come forward and tell the
government the real problems they are facing now, saying "We are
not interested in bailing them out but make policies to help them
out." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
