<HEADLINE> Death of 18 People Abroad Crashed Plane in Nepal Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior tourism ministry
official on Thursday denied an earlier report that all the 18
people on board a crashed passenger plane in western Nepal were
killed.
</P>
<P>
A duty officer at the Rescue and Coordination Center of the
capital's Tribhuvan International Airport said Thursday that two
or three rescue workers had reached the crash site at an altitude
of 12,000 feet (some 4,000 meters).
</P>
<P>
He said that except two female bodies, the rest were
unrecognizable because they were "in pieces."
</P>
<P>
Early Thursday morning, a rescue center duty officer said that
the rescue team had only 15 meters left to the crash site.
</P>
<P>
However, Secretary Dipendra Purush Dhakal at the Ministry of
Tourism and Civil Aviation denied that the rescue team had reached
the site. "Don't believe in rumors," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated Twin Otter aircraft lost contact five minutes
after it took off last Friday in Jomsom, western Nepal. Those
abroad includes three crew members and three Indians.
</P>
<P>
It was found crashed into pieces Tuesday morning, but rescue
efforts were hampered by rain and thick fog.
</P>
<P>
The radio and television said that army personnel managed
Wednesday to build a helipad near the crash site and 12 persons
were dropped there.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft was leased by the private-owned Lumbini Airways.
</P>
