<HEADLINE> Rusedski Advances in Hamlet Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Briton Greg Rusedski, last
year's U.S. Open runner-up, overcame a broken right shoe at the
crucial stage to beat Brazil's Fernando Meligeni in straight sets
on Wednesday in the Hamlet Cup tennis tournament in New York.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski, who made his second appearance after injurying his
left ankle seven weeks ago, changed his shoes with the score
levelled at 2-2 in the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
"The heel actually fell off," Rusedski said. "I can't help it
if my shoe fell apart and I certainly did not want to risk
another broken ankle. I showed it to the officials and actually
pulled on the shoe to show them the break."
</P>
<P>
David Prinosil of Germany, who entered the tourney after
Yegeny Kafelnikov pulled out due to an injury, beat defending
champion and French Open champion Carlos Moya of Spain 6-2, 6-2.
Moya is ranked 10th in the world to Prinosil's 81st.
</P>
<P>
Russian Matt Safin, an 18-year-old rookie on the ATP Tour,
reached the quarterfinals by beating Filip Dewulf of Belgium
7-6(8-6), 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Safin, who started the year ranked 204th, climbed to No. 72
last Monday mainly thanks to his victories over Andre Agassi and
Gustavo Kuerten in the French Open.  
</P>
