<HEADLINE> Davenport Wins, Sanchez-vicario Upset in Pilot Pen Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Lindsay Davenport
of the United States saved her strength with a walk-over victory
while third seed Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario of Spain was upset by
an unseeded player today at the Pilot Pen tennis tournament in
New Haven, Connecticut, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, the defending champion, is seeking her fourth
straight title this year, walked over Spain's Virginia
Ruano-Pascual. But Sanchez-Vicario was surprisingly beaten by
Julie Halard-Decugis of France 6-7 (6-8), 2-6 in a bizarre match
postponed hours by rain.
</P>
<P>
Halard-Decugis, who missed most of 1997 due to knee, shoulder
an wrist injuries, said she was making some mistakes in the
beginning. "I just tired to focus more. There was so many going
to the eyes and mouth and everywhere, and it was difficult to
play." By the middle of the second set, both had to contend with
the unsettling cloud of gnats.
</P>
<P>
"I make too many unforced errors. She played much more
consistent than myself," Sanchez-Vicario said.
</P>
<P>
Seeded second at next week's U.S. Open, Davenport could
overtake Martina Hingis of Switzerland as the world's top-ranked
player if she wins the final Grand Slam event of the year. She
has won 12 straight matches, including a three-set triumph over
Hingis in the Acura Classic final two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Novotna, who won Wimbledon this year and ranked third in the
world, beat American Chanda Rubin today 6-1, 7-5. Novotna has won
four titles this year while compiling a 42-9 season record.
</P>
<P>
In other matches, Germany's Anke Huber knocked off sixth seed
Patty Schnyder of Switzerland 7-5, 7-6 (7-2). Schnyder leads the
WTA Tour with five singles titles this year. Huber will meet
Davenport in the next round.
</P>
<P>
No. 7 Amanda Coetzer of South Africa ousted Russian teenager
Anna Kournikova 1-6, 6-4, 7-5, to set up a quarterfinal meeting
with fourth seed Steffi Graf of Germany.
</P>
<P>
Graf, tuning up for her long-awaited return to the U.S. Open,
accepted a wild-card entry into this event, which she won three
times. Despite being ranked 38th in the world, Graf will be an
eighth seed at next week's Open in New York. She missed last
year's Grand Slam event after undergoing season-ending knee
surgery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
