<HEADLINE> Egypt Sends Relief Aid to Sudan, Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- An Egypt Air flight took off early
Thursday for Khartoum carrying 40 tonnes of medicines, food and
other relief aid to help relieve the suffering of the people in
the famine-stricken Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The aid was ordered by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and was
aimed at expressing Cairo's solidarity with its neighboring Sudan,
the Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another planeload of relief supplies is scheduled
to sent to Kenya on Friday, which suffered a terror bombing attack
against the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi on August 7.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak had already dispatched to Kenya a medical team, led by
Minister of Health Ismail Sallam, to help treat the victims of the
blast of the American Embassy in Nairobi, which killed over 200
people and wounded thousands of others.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's 15-year civil war, combined with famine, has left 2.5
million people suffering from lack of food.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the U.S. missile strike destroyed a
pharmaceutical factory near Khartoum, which provided the country
with 50 percent of its needs of medicines
</P>
<P>
The U.S. launched the attacks in what it claimed retaliation
against the twin bombings against its embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania on August 7.
</P>
<P>
Washington, which has been accusing Sudan of sponsoring
international terrorism, claimed the factory was manufacturing
chemical weapons agents that could be used by Islamic militants to
launch new attacks against U.S. targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
