<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Pandas Presented to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-year-old female giant
panda, Jiajia, and male giant panda, An'an, 12, winners of a
so-called "beauty contest" for the endangered species will be
moved to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) by
early next year.
</P>
<P>
The giant pandas will be moved upon completion of their new
enclosure in the Hong Kong Park.
</P>
<P>
Jiajia and An'an, the central government's special gifts to
Hong Kong, were selected from over 100 giant pandas housed in
inland zoos or giant panda breeding centers.
</P>
<P>
An official from China's Giant Panda Protection Project office
said that health, appearance, age and character were the main
criteria in selecting China's "Miss and Mister Giant Panda
Contest."
</P>
<P>
The two giant pandas are currently enjoying meals constisting
of milk, vitamins, eggs and various special nutritious food items,
in addition to their staple food bamboo.
</P>
<P>
Zoologists note that their initial diets in Hong Kong will
consist of food shipped from inland areas. However, they will be
introduced to local food once acclimated to the new surroundings.
</P>
<P>
The zoologists are confident the pair will accept bamboo grown
in Hong Kong since giant pandas housed in zoos in southern China
readily adapt to local bamboo.
</P>
<P>
Jiajia currently weighs over 80 kg and An'an tips the scales at
90 kilograms. Both of the orphaned animals were in poor health
when found.
</P>
<P>
Jiajia has been housed in the Wolong Giant Panda Protection
Center in southwest China's Sichuan Province, with An'an housed in
the city of Shenzhen which neighbors the HKSAR..
</P>
<P>
Zoologists point out that the fertility of giant pandas is
generally quite low. Nonetheless, Jiajia birthed six cubs between
1992-1996, with five of her offspring thriving as of this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
