<HEADLINE> Sihanouk: Constitutional Change Possible Only With Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's King Norodom
Sihanouk said Wednesday that the three major elected parties need
to reach an agreement on Constitutional amendment in order to make
it easier to form a new government, Cambodia Daily reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The King said in an interview that "an amendment to our
Constitution will be possible if the presidents of the three big
parties, elected by our respected and beloved people in the July
26 elections, all agree to have such an amendment."
</P>
<P>
The King, meanwhile, thanked the confidence Surin Pitsuwan,
Minister of Foreign Affairs of Thailand, placed in him. Surin
Pitsuwan suggested the King intervene in order to calm the
passions and to put the current political crisis in Phnom Penh to
an end.
</P>
<P>
"At the present time, an action or initiative of King Norodom
Sihanouk is conceivable and possible only if Hun Sen, Prince
Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy request me together to enter into action
to try to carry out this or that amendment, with their
examinations, in the supreme interests of our nation," the King
said.
</P>
<P>
The faxed interview from the King's cabinet came a day after
news broke out that the ruling Cambodia People's Party is working
to convene members of the outgoing parliament to try to change the
Constitution and break the political deadlock that has intensified
this week.
</P>
<P>
But opposition leaders and many analysts doubt that the CPP
could rally enough Funcinpec and Buddhist Liberal Democratic Party
(BLDP) lawmakers in the outgoing parliament and make the change
before the current assembly's mandate ends at September 24. It
needs 70 percent of the 120 members present to convene an assembly
meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that King Sihanouk's statement carries weight,
as he is one of the three people, besides the prime minister and
the chairman of the National Assembly, allowed to initiate a
change in the Constitution under Article 123. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
