<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Urge More Public Awareness to Battle Heart Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- More than 42,000 cardiological
experts called for greater public awareness to reduce heart
disease as they concluded a five-day cardiology conference here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The experts warned myocardial infarction and cardiovascular
disorders are still the "top killers" in Western countries, and
while considerable progress has been made in the last two decades,
harmful side-effects remain a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
They urged governments to increase financial support for
cardiological research and to give more publicity to the issue,
stressing that without public health awareness and active
prevention, even the most remarkable medical achievements would be
to no avail.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the 20th European Cardiology Conference
reported their latest efforts to combat the disease, including a
new cure based on gene technology and new medicines such as
Mivazerel, which will be on the market soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
