<HEADLINE> Boeing's Delta III Rocket Explodes After Blast-off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Boeing's newest rocket,
the Delta III rocket, exploded during its inaugural flight at Cape
Canaveral, Florida, Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The 12-story rocket was blasted off at 9:17 p.m. local time and
exploded a little over a minute with the 225-million-U.S.-dollar
Galaxy communication satellite on board.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time in two weeks that an unmaned U.S.
rocket exploded.
</P>
<P>
Boeing officials said they didn't know what had happeded to the
rocket and would launch an immediate investigation into the
accident.
</P>
<P>
The Delta III, powered by nine strap-on boosters, a usual core
engine and an extra large upper-stage engine, is designed to lift
more than 8,400 pounds of payload into a 22,300-mile-high orbit,
two times the payload of the Delta II.
</P>
<P>
The 8,500-plus-pound Galaxy satellite aboard the rocket was to
provide television and data services to the U.S. and the Caribbean
by the end of September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
