<HEADLINE> Russian Crisis Has No Direct Effect on Bulgaria: Dealer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said there might be more tangible adverse effects caused by
the crisis in a longer perspective because of the sharp decline in
the rates of loans and/or securities in transition.
</P>
<P>
Tension on the German foreign currency market (Germany is
Russia's largest creditor) and on the US dollar markets in South
America (Brazil, Mexico, Argentine) may result in fluctuations in
the exchange rate between the German mark and the U.S. dollar,
which will also affect the exchange rate between German mark and
the Bulgarian lev.
</P>
<P>
According to Popov, the exchange rates have stood firm for over
a month in the ranges of 995.0 - 995.20 leva against 1 German mark
and 1,793.0 to 1,795.1 against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Former Vice Governor of the Central Bank Mileti Mladenov said
that Bulgaria's economy and its foreign exchange market will not
collapse under the consequences of the Russian crisis.
</P>
<P>
He added that the country's negative trade balance with Russia,
its large foreign debt in the depreciation of the loan
instruments, and the increased pressure on the German mark are the
factors that may have a more radical effect on Bulgaria. 
