<HEADLINE> Peshawar-Based Afghan Universities Ordered to Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The government of Pakistan's
North West Frontier Province has ordered the closing of half a
dozen unauthorized educational institutions in the provincial
capital of Peshawar being run by some Afghan nationals.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government issued the order late Wednesday to
wind up those unauthorized universities, medical colleges and
computer training centers which have been established by some
Afghan refugees over the years and issue degrees and certificates
to Afghan nationals as well as Pakistanis.
</P>
<P>
According to independent estimates, each of the illegal
educational institutions being run by the Afghan nationals in
Peshawar has enrolled more than 200 students, making a total of
more than 2,000 regular students both Afghan and Pakistani at the
institutions in Peshawar alone.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that there are more than 100 educational
institutions including religious schools run by the Afghan
refugees in the province while almost the same number exists in
other parts of Pakistan including Balochistan province and the
Federal Administered Tribal Areas.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman of the government of North West
Frontier Province, the decision to close those educational
institutions has been made at the request of the Taliban militia,
who want Afghan students to seek admission in authorized Afghan
universities.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Wali Naeemi, a senior Taliban official based in
Peshawar, when asked to comment on the development, said, "We are
trying to find a solution to the problem related to Afghan
students in Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
He maintained that none of the educational institutions being
run by Afghan refugees in Pakistan was affiliated with Pakistani
institutions nor the universities and schools were recognized by
the Taliban authorities.
</P>
<P>
"Our government neither recognizes these institutions being run
(by Afghan refugees) in Pakistan nor accepts their degrees,"
Naeemi said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Taliban authorities have offered a comprehensive
package to Afghan students and asked those studying in the
educational institutions being run by Afghan refugees in Pakistan
to seek admission for studies in Afghanistan's universities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
