<HEADLINE> Indian Opposition Party Prepares Economic Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- India's biggest opposition
party the Congress has prepared a 30-page report on the economic
agenda in a bid to improve the country's present bad economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
The report will be the basis of discussions at the forthcoming
three-day party session in Madhya Pradesh early next month,
Congress sources said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the combination of the fallout of the nuclear
explosion in May this year and a "confused, directionless" budget
for 1998-99 of the government has made the "sentiment on India
negative amongst all investors."
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "Current Economic Challenges," said that
even a planning commission has not been constituted and the Ninth
Five-Year Plan (1998-2002) is in "abeyance."
</P>
<P>
Both the revenue and fiscal deficits in the country are at
unsustainable levels and it is imperative that a three- to
five-year program for reducing the fiscal deficit to less than 5
percent of the GDP and bringing the revenue deficit to close to
zero without affecting growth and social welfare is put into
place, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Congress' economic agenda revolves around "one fundamental
objective, namely, the abolition, within our own generation, of
poverty" and the creation of "adequate employment opportunities"
so that the Indian people can have a decent standard of living.
</P>
<P>
The party will also try to ensure "a minimum standard of
education and skills for all Indians, particularly those belonging
to the weaker section, the report further said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
