<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Libya to Surrender Lockerbie Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States said that
Libya should quickly handover two suspects accused of blowing up a
Pan Am airliner if it takes seriously the U.S.-British proposal.
</P>
<P>
"If the Libyans are serious, we would expect the next step to
be the (U.N.) secretary general's notification that the suspects
have been transported to the Hague and are in Dutch custody," an
administration official said Wednesday from Martha's Vineyard,
where U.S. President Bill Clinton is vacationing.
</P>
<P>
The official made the remark following a Libyan foreign
ministry statement, which said Libya would deal "positively" with
the U.S.-British proposal to try the two Libyan suspects in the
Hague, Netherlands, with Scottish judges applying Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
The official said the United States had received reports that
the Libya had accepted the proposal.
</P>
<P>
"If this means that Libya intends to surrender the two suspects
to Dutch custody we would consider this a positive development,"
he said. "However, if the Libyan statement signifies an attempt to
negotiate the terms of the trial, we would remind the Libyan
government that the terms are nonnegotiable."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the State Department said the Libyan statement was
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
It "does not specifically state that Libya is prepared -- as
called for in the U.N. Security Council resolutions -- to promptly
turn the suspects over for trial," State Department spokesman
James Foley said.
</P>
<P>
"The Libyan statement falls short of what U.N. Security Council
resolutions require," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, Libya asked the U.N. Security Council to
delay endorsing the U.S.-British proposal, saying it would need
time to study it.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the Libyan request, White House spokesman Barry
Toiv said the United States did not see any reason for the delay
on Libya's part as "the proposal accords with what they said they
would agree to in the past." 
</P>
</TEXT>
