<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calcium May Soothe premenstrual Syndrome Symptoms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- A new study shows that women
might dramatically reduce the premenstrual syndrome (PMS) by
taking Tums tablet which contains calcium, the Associated
Press reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by St. Lukes-Roosevelt Hospital Center,
suggested that a daily supplement of 1,200-milligram doses of
calcium reduced the symptoms by 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the study of 497 women, half of them were given four
chewable calcium carbonate tablets daily for a total of 1,200
milligrams of calcium. The other half received tablets without
calcium.
</P>
<P>
The results showed a drop in symptoms among those who took the
pills with calcium.
</P>
<P>
The PMS symptoms include bloating, pain, irritability, food
cravings, malaise, migraines and mood swings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Hurricane Bonnie Lashes U.S. East Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane Bonnie lashed the
East Coast of the United States Wednesday afternoon with stinging
rain and powerful winds that forced nearly 500,000 residents and
tourists to evacuate the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
The storm swamped roads, knocked out power to at least 240,000
residents and peeled a roof from a hospital in the Wilmington
area, a southern coast town of North Carolina. There were no
immediate reports of deaths or serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the storm also created new inlets that cut two
small barrier islands in half.
</P>
<P>
The storm struck the coastal area from the Atlantic early in
the afternoon at Cape Fear, near the South Carolina state line. It
slowed from 20 to 13 kilometers per hour (kph) as it came ashore.
</P>
<P>
As of 7:30 p.m. EDT (2330 GMT), Bonnie was centered near Wrightsville
Beach, about 32 kilometers north of Cape Fear.
</P>
<P>
Wind along the coast reached sustained speeds of 120 kph at
Southport, with occasional gusts elsewhere hitting 160 kph in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Sea water three-meters above normal tide level was reported in
some areas Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The storm was expected eventually to veer to the northeast and
move out to sea near the North Carolina-Virginia line.
</P>
<P>
National Hurricane Center officials warned that the
650-kilometer-wide storm would take 30 hours to move out of the
centrally hit area.
</P>
<P>
More than 330,000 people were ordered to evacuate North
Carolina's coastal islands and about 200,000 more, including
120,000 tourists, were urged to leave South Carolina's two
northernmost coastal counties in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
A state of emergency was declared in Virginia and hurricane
warnings were in effect across a 800-kilometer stretch of
coastline, from Chincoteague, Virginia, to Edisto Beach, South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
The Navy sent about 40 ships at the Norfolk Naval Base out to
sea to weather the storm, including the aircraft carriers USS
Enterprise and the USS Roosevelt. Commercial ships were barred
from entering Virginia's Hampton Roads port.
</P>
<P>
The last hurricane, Hurricane Fran, struck the Wilmington area
in September 1996, causing 24 deaths and 5.2 billion U.S. dollars
in damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
