<HEADLINE> Austria Mulling Indemnity from Italy over Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 26 (Xinhua)-- Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima
held a cabinet meeting Wednesday night, discussing losses caused
by Italy's misreporting over Austrian beef, and possible indemnity.
</P>
<P>
In late July, the relevant authorities in Italy reported to the
Commission of the European Union that they found beef imported
from Austria was contaminated with a cancer-producing hormone and
announced a halt to beef imports from Austria.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Austria authorities began to investigate the
incident and warned the public off beef products. But the test by
Austria itself showed that the exported beef didn't contain any
harmful hormones.
</P>
<P>
On August 25, the Dutch laboratory appointed by the European
Commission confirmed the test results of Austria. Italy thus
canceled the beef ban.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Agriculture Ministry suggested that the beef row
invoked by Italy cost Austria 16.8 million U.S. dollars. Besides,
another 4.8 million dollars are needed to publicize at home and
abroad to restore the reputation of Austrian beef.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor Klima said Wednesday that he had written to the
prime minister of Italy, seeking his assistance to solve problems
resulting from the beef row. 
</P>
</TEXT>
