<HEADLINE> Dhaka Seeks Foreign Assistance for Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has appealed to its
donor countries and agencies for 508.39 million U.S. dollars and
1.38 million tons of food for emergency relief and post-flood
rehabilitation programs, press reports here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to representatives of the donors on Wednesday, Finance
Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria said the devastating flood had caused
an economic disaster in the country, as "it has caused disruption
in all sorts of economic activities."
</P>
<P>
"This has become an emergency now and our government has
decided to seek foreign assistance to combat the situation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Kibria noted that nothing was spared in the affected areas
because of the unprecedented lengthy flood. "At the initial stage,
it was a natural flood like other years and we had the capability
to cope with it. But right now, it is just not possible," he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He urged the donors to respond quickly to the government's
requests, as the agricultural activities would start immediately
as soon as the waters recede.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, food, communications, fisheries, livestock and
water resources are among as the worst affected sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has committed 200,000 tons of food grain
while Denmark has pledged 14 million dollars for repair and
rehabilitation of the Dhaka-Aricha highway, a Finance Ministry
release said.
</P>
<P>
Other donors such as Britain, Canada, Japan, and Germany have
also provided or agreed to provide assistance to the country.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister asked the donors to make the delivery of
assistance quickly as "we want to start rehabilitation work as
soon as the flood waters recede."
</P>
<P>
According to official estimates, the floods have so far left
more than 400 people dead and nearly 30 million homeless and
caused damage worth 222.5 million dollars to agriculture,
infrastructure and other sectors in 55 out of the country's 64
districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
