<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Japan Implement Seed Bank Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Japan have been
jointly implementing a seed bank project in Yezin, Pyinmana
Township in central part of the country, under their technical
cooperation program.
</P>
<P>
The five-year Japanese-aided project, which began in the
1997-98 fiscal year, is carried out between the Central
Agricultural Research Department of Myanmar Agriculture Services
and the Japan International Cooperation Agency, the official
newspaper New Light of Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the Joint Coordinating Committee of the
Seed Bank Project, held here on Wednesday, discussed quality
tests, reproduction and records of crop strains and installation
and use of equipment.
</P>
<P>
In July, the Japanese government provided a grant aid of 5.7
million U.S. dollars, the latest of its kind, to Myanmar to help
the country increase grain production in the border areas.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' Bilateral Economic Cooperation Committee
also met in Yangon in May to seek more ways to promote the
cooperation especially in trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Japan had invested over 206
million dollars in 17 permitted projects in Myanmar by the end of
April this year, ranking ninth among 23 countries or regions which
have a total of 7 billion dollars of investment in the country.
</P>
