<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Exports to Russia Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Italy's exports to Russia increased
by 32 percent in the first quarter despite ruble's steep
devaluation and worries that the Russian economy might be out of
control.
</P>
<P>
The exports were valued at 1.7 trillion lire (1 billion
U.S. dollars), according to trade sources. Imports in the same
period fell by 4.8 percent to 1.842 trillion lire (1.04 billion
dollars), trimming Italy's trade deficit with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Energy products, oil, natural gas and other raw materials
accounted for 60 percent of the Italian exports, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a total of 768 joint ventures between the two
countries had been established by the end of last year. Italian
groups with interest in Russia include Fiat, Telecom Italia, Fata,
Breda, Merloni and Parmalat, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between the two countries stood at 6.2 billion
dollars in 1997, up 20 percent over 1996, making Italy Russia's
third largest trade partner behind the United States and Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
