<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Czech Republic Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment in the
Czech Republic reached 589 million U.S. dollars in the first half
of this year, a 25 percent increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to latest statistics from the Czech National Bank,
approximately 55 percent of the investment went into the financial
and insurance sectors. Britain, America and Germany were the main
investors, contributing 48.3 percent, 20.8 percent and 11.8
percent of the total investment respectively.
</P>
<P>
Since the country adopted the policy of reform toward a market
economy in 1990, the Czech Republic has taken 7.6 billion
U.S. dollars in direct foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
However, over recent years, the annual investment in the Czech
Republic has obviously declined, to 1.4 billion U.S. dollars in
1996 and 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 separately, roughly half
of the size in 1995.
</P>
<P>
As a stimulus package, the Czech government formulated a set of
preferential policies to encourage foreign investment in April,
including a five-year tax exemption on earnings for investors each
investing more than 25 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The preferential policies also cover the exemption of tax on
the import of high-tech equipment, the establishment of free
tariff zones and the extension of interest free loans to those who
expropriate land for use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
