<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oldest Irrigation System Being Phased Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Turpan Prefecture of
the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region are phasing out the
1,700-year-old karez, an irrigation system of wells connected by
underground channels, and replacing it with the more efficient
electric pumps.
</P>
<P>
Some of the karez have been turned into scenic spots or can be
seen in museums. They are usually three to four kilometers long
and the underground channel brings water from the nearby Tianshan
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
The system was invented the Uygur ethnic group as something
suited to the dry climate and has played an important role in the
oasis in this land of unbearable heat.
</P>
<P>
But, the old irrigation system is only geared to small
production and was doomed by growing agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang had more than 1,500 karez in the 1950s, over 1,100 of
which were in Turpan. But the figure in the prefecture is now
about 600, and there are fewer karez builders around.
</P>
<P>
To make the most of its limited water resources, Turpan
introduced a water coupon system for irrigation in 1995, and other
methods like sprinklers to make farmers more aware of the need to
save water.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture has built 14 reservoirs and more than 4,000
kilometers of channels that can irrigate three times the amount of
farmland that they did in the past.
</P>
<P>
However, local people still like the karez and have set up a
karez research society and exhibition hall. The local government
has also ruled that no well can be dug within 400 meters of an
existing karez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
