<HEADLINE> Ukraine Suggests Extending Term of National Debt Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian government suggested
Wednesday that holders of short-term national debt bonds exchange
them for long-term liabilities to help relieve the financial
difficulties it is facing.
</P>
<P>
People who hold bonds with a maturity date of less than one
year were "asked" to extend the term "voluntarily" to 1.5 to 5.5
years, payable every half a year.
</P>
<P>
Yields, guaranteed to be independent of the exchange rate of
hryvina to the dollar, will be 40 percent per year in hryvina
for the first two lots of bonds and will float for the rest.
</P>
<P>
Domestic bonds the Ukrainian government issued have accumulated
to 14 billion hryvinas (about 7 billion U.S. dollars). It has
also borrowed more than 12 billion U.S. dollars from abroad.
</P>
<P>
It needs annually more than 2 billion dollars, which is a heavy
burden to finance, to pay debts at maturity.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of 10 banks, the biggest holders of short-term bonds,
signed agreements immediately following the recommendation to
exchange them for long-term bonds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
