<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank to Be Restructured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand will be
restructured to ensure maximum efficiency while maintaining
independence in setting monetary policies, according to its
governor Chatumongol Sonakul.
</P>
<P>
A committee of international experts and former central bankers
was helping draft a study on restructuring, Chatumongol was quoted
Thursday by The Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The central bank would maintain independence from the Finance
Ministry and the government in setting monetary policies, as well
as supervision and examination of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
To improve staff effectiveness, central bank officials would be
encouraged to meet regularly with local financiers to exchange
ideas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another program to upgrade the ability of auditors and
examiners has also been established.
</P>
<P>
"In the long term, the Bank of Thailand will redirect its
responsibility toward managing price stability, to allow the
private sector to operate in a supportive environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's economic crisis could be attributed to the central
bank's failure in the past to independently perform its duties, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The term of the governor should be fixed, he suggested, to
further ensure independence. But the authority of the governor
would also be counterbalanced by the Senate and members of the
Court of Directors appointed by the government.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the governor's authority would be well
counterbalanced by the political authorities. The governor should
make a general statement on policy to the Senate each year," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Senate was politically neutral when compared with the Lower
House or the government, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
