<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   American U.N. Weapons Inspector Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Scott Ritter, an
American U.N. weapons inspector in Iraq resigned his U.N. post on
Wednesday, the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM)
chief Richard Butler said.
</P>
<P>
Ritter's resignation comes at a time when U.N. weapons
inspection in Iraq has been blocked by Iraq's August 5
announcement to suspend its cooperation with UNSCOM in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Ritter's departure had been accepted and took effect
immediately, said Richard Butler, Executive Chairman of UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
In his letter of resignation, Ritter, an expert on methods of
concealment and missiles, expressed his dissatisfaction that the
Security Council of the United Nations was so soft that it had
failed to take a tougher stand on the latest Iraqi impasse over
arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the Council for no longer willing or capable of
the implementation of its own law.
</P>
<P>
Ritter also accused U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan of
allowing his office to become a "sounding board for Iraqi
grievances, real or imagined."
</P>
<P>
Ritter has been with UNSCOM for six years and has been accused
by Iraq of being a U.S. spy. He was in Baghdad early this month
when the disarmament talks between Butler and Iraq's Deputy Prime
Minister Tareq Aziz collapsed.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced on August 5 that it would no longer cooperate
with UNSCOM until it has restructured and moved its headquarters
from New York to Geneva or Vienna.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council on August 6 called Iraq's announcement
"totally unacceptable" and urged it to reverse its decision. But
Iraq reiterated on several occasions that there would be no
changes in its decision until all its concerns are addressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
