<HEADLINE> Panama to Invest 44 Million USD in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Panama will invest 44
million U.S. dollars in agriculture for technological
improvements, Panamanian President Ernesto Perez Balladares said
in his weekly report published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"This support is in response to the challenge imposed by
globalization of the economy and the elimination of government
patronage," said Balladares.
</P>
<P>
The new challenge calls for better quality merchandise that can
compete in the international market, Balladares added.
</P>
<P>
As part of the effort, tomato and corn fields will be changed
to fields for watermelons, melons, and black beans, which are more
profitable in the markets, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Tomato producers will receive a grant worth 2 million dollars,
and financial aid in the form of loans worth 4.8 million dollars,
so they can transform 700 hectares in three years," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, corn producers will receive 2.16 million dollars and
a direct investment, which will have to be reimbursed, of 6.77
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Supporting the producers now is guaranteeing them a prosperous
future and reliable food supplies and sources for the rest of the
country," Balladares said. 
</P>
