<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Jakarta Commander Investigated Over May Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Former Jakarta Military
Commander Major General Sjafrie Sjamsoeddin has testified before
members of the Joint Fact-Finding Team investigating the riots
that racked the capital in May, the Indonesian Observer reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting was merely to seek the general's clarification and
to consult him. We wanted to hear the security authorities'
version of what they did during the unrest," team member Bambang
Widjojanto was quoted by the paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sjafrie was questioned for nearly three hours on Wednesday,
Bambang said.
</P>
<P>
"Our questions centered around the methods used by the Direct
and Indirect Security Task Forces in dealing with the unrest. We
wanted to know what those methods were in concrete terms, how the
lines of command functioned, the strength of the security forces
deployed and why forces in the field had at one time asked for
reinforcements," he said.
</P>
<P>
The questions were addressed to Sjafrie because he was then the
Jakarta military commander, Bambang said, adding that Sjafrie was
not a suspect in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
The team was established by the government last month to
investigate reports that the May riots, in which more than 1,200
people were killed, were masterminded.
</P>
<P>
Sjafrie was replaced in early July and moved to the post of
territorial assistant to the Armed Forces chief of general staff.
</P>
<P>
Bambang said the team would summon several other officials in
connection with the incidents.
</P>
<P>
"We have not yet been able to draw any conclusions from the
meeting with Sjafrie as we still need information from others," he
said, adding that Sjafrie might be summoned again if more
information was needed from him.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of public figures, including the country's
largest Muslim organization Nahdlatul Ulama leader Abdurrahman
Wahid, intend to form an independent "Commission to Establish
Truth and National Reconciliation" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The commission in which foreign personalities would also be
invited to take part, aims to find out the truth about the human
rights abuses that allegedly occurred during the May riots and
attempt to bring about national reconciliation among Indonesians,
Wahid told reporters here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bambang said the political, moral, social and economic damage
caused to the nation by the riots was enormous and the image of
Indonesian society as a tolerant one was now in question at home
and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
