<HEADLINE> Panama to Build Traffic Tunnel Under Canal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 26 (xinhua) -- Panama is studying the
possibility of building a tunnel beneath the Panama Canal at a
cost of some 300 million dollars to reduce traffic pressure on the
Americas Bridge, a senior official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Public Works Minister Luis Blanco said his ministry has already
finished feasibility studies on the work. They expect to start
construction on the downstream tunnel in the near future in order
to have it in operation by 2003.
</P>
<P>
According to studies, it will take 2-3 years to complete the
project. The tunnel will connect the Capital city with the west
Sector.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that at the moment they are thinking about
ways to finance the project; they have not ruled out the
possibility of a government grant.
</P>
<P>
Blanco said that as soon as the financing is settled there
will be a bid offering, so different experienced construction
companies will be able to participate in the project.
</P>
<P>
The Minister pointed out that enlargement of the Americas
Bridge is not a viable or permanent solution against the
increasing traffic. He said it is essential to build an alternate
route.
</P>
<P>
Some 300,000 vehicles cross the Americas Bridge everyday
because Arraijan and Chorrera cities have developed many housing
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
