<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The devastating floods across China have now claimed 3,004
lives, and preliminary reports indicate that 29 provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities have been hit by the floods
to various degrees this year, and 21 million hectares of lands
have also been flooded.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao yesterday
afternoon while briefing the fourth meeting of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress, China's legislature,
on the most recent developments in the flood-fighting operations.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-President Hu Jintao visited Heilongjiang and Jilin
provinces in northeastern China on Tuesday and Wednesday and
expressed the thanks of the central government leaders to
civilians and soldiers fighting the on-going floods.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes the people will be confident of victory, try
to overcome their fatigue, and continue to work and defend the
dikes for a final victory of their endeavors.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji said yesterday that China
welcomes more people of vision from the US religious circle to
visit China.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remarks during a meeting with Marion Gordon "Pat"
Robertson, chairman of the Board of Christian Broadcast Network,
and his party.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing spoke with officials from central
government departments on Wednesday about disease control and
education in China's flood-ravaged areas.
</P>
<P>
Li told the meeting of officials that a special effort needs to
be made to prevent the outbreak of epidemic diseases and to see to
it that schools open on time in September in those areas.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A group of delegates from the International Federation of
Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies visited Jiangzhou in the city
of Jiujiang yesterday to assess the extent of flood damage.
</P>
<P>
-- Registration for elementary and middle school students is
under way despite flooding in Jiangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang Education Commission decided schools in the region
will begin on September 1, the traditional opening day for China's
elementary and middle schools.
</P>
<P>
-- O'kying Chilai, the 17th Garmaba Living Buddha of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, recently completed his basic study of Buddhism
in the Curbo Monastery near Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
The 14-year-old Buddha, has memorized more than 4,000 sutras,
or Buddhist prayers, and reached a fourth-grade level in Chinese
language studies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
