<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rice Import Raised to 4.1 Million Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
decided to boost the volume of its planned rice imports from 3.1
million tons to 4.1 million tons, Antara News Agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision to increase rice imports was made in connection
with Agriculture Ministry projections that rice production during
the rainy season would still not be sufficient to cover expected
rice supply gaps, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic rice production during the past rainy season would
fail to meet expected levels because of a combination of factors
including delays in distribution of subsidized fertilizers and
insufficiency of credits for rice farmers, the report quoted
National Logistics Agency Chief Beddu Amang as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the Agriculture Ministry, this year's rice
production would be about 46 million tons, or 86.9 percent of the
targeted 53 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Amang said some of the imported rice would be granted by
several countries and the rest would be borrowed while the
additional 1 million tons which had just been decided would be
bought under commercial terms through international tenders.
</P>
<P>
"The rice will be bought from a number of neighboring
countries, including Thailand, Vietnam, China, India and
Pakistan," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
