<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Shanghai People Visit Websites for Leisure and Shopping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 27 (Xinhua)-- "Shanghai Hotline," one of the
most popular websites in China, has been visited more than 10
million times since it was set up on November 22, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The website, according to Zhang Linde, general manager of
Shanghai Information Industry Co., Ltd., linked with six others in
China, have more than 40,000 subscribers and about 180,000 regular
visitors.
</P>
<P>
The number of daily average visitors has increased to 40,000
from several hundred only two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of cyberspace has also led more people
do their shopping on-line.
</P>
<P>
The Xinhua Bookstore on East Nanjing Road launched its site on
the hotline last May, the first on-line bookstore in the city.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jinhua, manager of the on-line bookstore, said that sales
volume has reached about 200,000 yuan from on-line sales, and the
monthly average is approaching 20,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
On-line flower shops, drugstores and booking offices are also
very active on the hotline website.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that department-store customers in Shanghai are
expected to decline by 20 to 30 percent by the end of this century
due to the growth of on-line shopping and electronic businesses.
</P>
<P>
The "Shanghai Hotline" will soon enlarge its capacity for the
third time, in an effort to boost the number of visitors to one
million daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
