<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Welcomes New IMF Disbursement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
welcomed a decision of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to
disburse to the country another 1 billion U.S. dollars in rescue
funds and praised the new aid as another boost to the national
currency.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry
Ginandjar Kartasasmita said here Wednesday that the IMF aid,
combined with returning confidence in the economy following the
government's action against ailing banks last week, had
contributed greatly to the strengthening of the rupiah against the
U.S. dollar over the last three days.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah rose to about 11,100 per dollar early this week, its
highest level since May when the currency fell to as low as 17,000
per dollar.
</P>
<P>
"More encouraging is that the rupiah has been strengthening
without any government market intervention," local leading
newspapers Thursday quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Since July last year, the rupiah has lost more than 80 percent
of its value against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has projected that the rupiah will
average 10,600 to the dollar during the current fiscal year which
ends next March.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully, the rupiah will gradually appreciate to 10,000 (per
dollar) later this year. But we prefer a gradual strengthening to
sharp, but volatile rise, because sharp fluctuations may spark
speculation," Ginandjar said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF Executive Board approved Tuesday the next
1-billion-dollar loan tranche to Indonesia as part of a 46 billion
U.S. dollar bailout package and praised the nation's efforts to
combat the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
As part of its economic and financial reform agreed by the IMF,
the Indonesian government launched major banking restructuring
moves on August 21 by merging four state banks, freezing the
operations of three ailing private banks and nationalizing four
other private banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
