<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SPF Heads of Government End Meeting in Micronesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The 29th South Pacific Forum
(SPF) heads of government meeting concluded in Micronesia on
Tuesday after reaching agreement on whale sanctuary, climate
change and some other issues.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of five out of the 16 member states of the forum were
absent from the two-day annual meeting held in Pohnpei, capital
of the Federated States of Micronesia, and they were prime
ministers of New Zealand, Australia, Papua New Guinea, the
Solomon Islands and Samoa, according to reports of the New Zealand
Press Association.
</P>
<P>
An agreement to plump for progress on climate change was
reached at the meeting with Tuvalu pushing for the final
communique to urge developed countries to act urgently to reduce
the emission of greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
In this year's final communique, the 16 Pacific Island states
"condemned the recent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan" and
gave their support to the development of a proposal for a South
Pacific whale sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided to allow New Caledonia observer status at
next year's meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also established rules for granting post-forum
dialogue partner status to interested countries, such as Mexico.
</P>
<P>
In its final document, the forum also referred to New Zealand
Foreign Minister Don McKinnon's possible bid for the post of
Commonwealth secretary-general, which becomes vacant in November
next year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed issues of trade liberalization and
economic reforms, the impact of the Asian financial crisis on the
Pacific region, aviation and regional security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
