<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Reports Rise in Use of Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The city of Shenzhen in south
China's Guangdong Province witnessed a monthly growth in the use
of overseas investment in the past seven months this year despite
the adverse influence of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
From January to July, the city, China's first of the five
special economic zones, approved 1,251 overseas-funded projects,
up 12.5 percent over the same period last year, and the
contractual volume of overseas investment was 1.684 billion
U.S. dollars, up 76.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the actual inflow of overseas
investment into the city was 1.596 billion U.S. dollars, up 1.6
percent, 69.4 percent of goal for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
The use of overseas investment in the zone over the past seven
months was characterized by increases in overseas loans for major
local projects and overseas direct investment, a rapid inflow of
investment from Hong Kong and Taiwan regions, increasing
investment from existing overseas-backed enterprises, and an
improved overseas investment structure coupled with a growing
number of technology-intensive projects, said a local official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relics Commemorating Sino-Japanese Sea Battle Martyrs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Three carved white marble pieces
have been identified as bases for steles commemorating martyrs in
a Sino-Japanese sea battle a century ago.
</P>
<P>
The steles, set up in a temple to honor the martyrs of the Jia
Wu Sea Battle in 1894, was ruined along with the temple by the
Japanese invaders in 1937.
</P>
<P>
The bases, the only remains of the temple, are each 130 cm
long, 80 cm wide and 60 cm high, and are decorated with reliefs of
dragons, waves, fish, shrimp, frogs and shells.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say that the bases will contribute to the
study of the navy of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), as well as
remind people of the history of Japanese invasions of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Foreign Ministry Urges Peace in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 26 (Xinhua)-- Italian Foreign Ministry said in a
statement Wednesday it continues to follow developments in the
ongoing civil war in Congo and hopes a peaceful solution will
be found by Congo and its neighboring African countries.
</P>
<P>
Italy and its European partners emphasized the need to safeguard
Congo's territorial integrity and avoid a regional extension of
the conflict, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
They also urged the parties involved to respect the fundamental
principles of international humanitarian law and of civilized
peoples, it said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the ministry's statement was released, the
Italian missionary congregations agency Misna reported more
massacres in Congo.
</P>
<P>
Misna said the killing spree in Urega in eastern Congo Monday
was not limited to the 37 people reported so far.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi Banyamulenge rebels also killed over 100 more
individuals in the area, according to Misna.
</P>
<P>
Italy has sent a first emergency humanitarian aid package in
the form of 10 tons of medical and surgical equipment for a
number of hospitals in Kinshasa and for the rehabilitation of the
important hospital of Ndjili.
</P>
<P>
Additional humanitarian initiatives to help alleviate the
war-stricken population of Congo are being planned, the ministry
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
