<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News at 0100 GMT, August 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States stated on Wednesday that the
indictment of seven Cuban Americans for allegedly plotting to kill
Cuban leader Fidel Castro does not mean a softening policy towards
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question during a regular briefing, State
Department Deputy Spokesman James Foley said the idea that the
indictment shows U.S. changed its Cuba policies is "really
ridiculous."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Justice Department announced the seven Cuban
Americans were indicted in Puerto Rico for planning to kill Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
Some Cuban exiles in Miami are accusing the U.S. government is
trying to defend Castro himself, not his government.
</P>
<P>
"The indictments... were the outcome of an independent federal
law-enforcement investigation. Any change in our policy towards
Cuba would... be wholly dependent on fundamental systemic
democratic change in Cuba of a kind we certainly have not seen,"
said Foley. (US-Cuba)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Stocks in New York fell sharply Wednesday, shaken
by the rattling global markets stemming from discouraging
developments in Japan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average finished 79.30 points lower at
8,523.35 after sliding as much as 135 points in the morning. The
Dow, which gained just 36 points Tuesday, is about 800 points
below the record 9,337.97 set on July 17.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 8.66 to 1,084.19, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 30.08 to 1,768.09.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly a 4-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling
671.86 million shares, up slightly from Tuesday's 663.77 million.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 5.45 to 539.56, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 13.03 to 633.83.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 9.34 to
380.42. (New York-Stocks Fall)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Libya Wednesday accepted a U.S.-British proposal for a
trial of two Libyan suspects in the 1988 Lockerbie bombing of a
Pan Am flight in the Hague, the Netherlands, before Scottish
Judges under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
This raises the hope that the six-year-old U.N. air and arms
embargo against Libya could be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the acceptance of the offer, a Libyan Foreign
Ministry statement carried by the Libyan news agency JANA said the
ministry "stresses the need to lift the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
The embargo as well as certain financial and travel
restrictions were imposed in 1992 after Libya refused to hand over
the two Libyan suspects in the bombing, which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have long urged Libya to hand over the two
suspects to stand trial in eighther of the two countries. But
Libya refused to turn over the suspects, contending that the trial
should be held to ensure its justness.
</P>
<P>
Washington and London announced on Monday their proposal to
allow the two Libyans to be tried in a third country.
(Libya-Lockerbie Bombing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The exchange rate is ranging between 8.8 and 9.57
rubles for one U.S. dollar on Wednesday despite the invalidation
of dollar trading at the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange
(MICEX), the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Some exchange offices change the rate five times on Wednesday
morning, saying demand exceeds supply greatly.
</P>
<P>
However, the growing dollar selling rate has not changed
Russia's financial situation since most of the offices have no
U.S. currency in cash.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, quotations of gas giant Gazprom shares drop
by 14 percent at noon time at the Moscow Stock Exchange with one
unit fetching 1.05 rubles.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow Stock Exchange index drops by 9.17 percent as
compared with that of Tuesday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There was a sharp increase in interest in Gazprom share in the
previous two days as Viktor Chernomyrdin, president of Gazprom,
was appointed acting prime minister. (Russia-Ruble) 
</P>
</TEXT>
