<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Advance into Champions League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Manchester United advanced to
the first round proper of the European Champions league after
holding LKS Lodz to a 0-0 draw in their second qualifying round
second leg match on Wednesday, preserving their two goal
advantage from the first leg at home.
</P>
<P>
The match was dull and neither side showed a great deal of
invention or penetration in Poland.
</P>
<P>
As expected Lodz attacked from the first whistle and after 30
seconds Rafal Niznik turned Denis Irwin before unleashing a 25-ya
rd shot which whizzed just past Peter Schmeichel's far post.
</P>
<P>
The lively Niznik then knocked the ball past United skipper
Roy Keane but the alert Ronny Johnsen read the situation to clear
the danger.
</P>
<P>
United came more into the game and David Beckham sent a
free-kick wide of the goal from 25 yards out.
</P>
<P>
After 17 minutes, David Beckham tried to test Lodz's defence
with another free kick, but he hit his effort against the wall
and goalkeeper Boguslaw Wyparlo easily caught the ball.
</P>
<P>
Minutes later Teddy Sheringham should have done better with a
header from a Ryan Giggs corner, but the England striker headed
weakly past the post.
</P>
<P>
Peter Schmeichel, who was playing his 25th Champions' League
game to climb to third in United's all-time appearance list, pr
oduced a fine interception to cut out Niznik's ball with Tomasz
Wieszczycki waiting to pounce.
</P>
<P>
United carved out another opening when Roy Keane found Beckham
in space on the right and Sheringham just failed to connect with
his inviting cross as he closed in on goal.
</P>
<P>
United re-jigged their attack when they brought on Tottenham
and Everton target Ole Gunnar Solskjaer for Giggs after 64
minutes. But his appearance did nothing to liven a dull game.
</P>
<P>
The game dribbled to its inevitable conclusion with United
having nothing to gain from a goal and Lodz producing little
invention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bucks Fire Head Coach Chris Ford </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Milwaukee Bucks today
fired coach Chris Ford, eight days after the Sacramento Kings
dismissed coach Eddie Jordon.
</P>
<P>
"We just decided to go in a different direction," said Bucks
general manager Bob Weinhauer at a news conference today. "We
felt that we needed to make greater improvement and we believe
that a change will accelerate that process."
</P>
<P>
Ford scored a 69-95 record in two years as Bucks coach. But
despite his lack of success, it appeared that Ford would serve
out the final year of his three-year contract when the Bucks
opted not to make a change before the July 1 lockout was
instituted.
</P>
<P>
"As far as the timing, there is no good time to make a
change,"said Weinhauer. "But those candidates that were there in
June are still there today. I believe only one job was filled in
Seattle."
</P>
<P>
However, Weinhauer did not specify any possible candidates for
the position so far. "We have identified a small group of
outstanding candidates for the head coaching position and intend
to make a decision in the very near future," Weinhauer added.
</P>
<P>
The Bucks also fired assistant coach Dick Versace, but have
made no decision on the status of assistants Jim Todd and Mike
Woodson.
</P>
<P>
The 49-year-old Ford was hired in 1996 by Bucks. He previously
served as coach of the Boston Celtics for five years and led the
team to four playoff appearances before coming to Milwaukee. In
his first year, the Celtics finished 56-26, but lost in six games
in the Eastern Conference semifinals. Ford has a career coaching
record of 291-283. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
