<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Begins Bid for Record Against Goellner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Pete Sampras of the
United States will begin his quest for a record-tying 12th Grand
Slam tournament singles title next week when he opposes Marc
Goellner of Germany in opening round at the U.S. Open tennis cha
mpionships in New York.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who has won five Wimbledon and two Australian Open
titles, will attempt to win the U.S. Open for the fifth time and
join former Australian star Roy Emerson with a record 12 career
Grand Slam titles.
</P>
<P>
But standing between Sampras and history could be long-time
rival Andre Agassi of the United States, the eighth seed. The two
could meet in the quarterfinals. Agassi has beaten Sampras twice
in their three meetings this season.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who won Wimbledon crown this year, won the U.S. Open
in 1990, 1993, 1994 and 1996, was upset by Petr Korda of the
Czech Republic in the fourth round last year. The 27-year-old
Sampras is the seventh consecutive American to be seeded first at
the Open.
</P>
<P>
Play begins Monday at the National Tennis Center in New York
and the schedule of first round play will be announced during the
weekend following the completion of qualifying competition, which
started yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Second seed Marcelo Rios of Chile will open against Daniel
Vacek of the Czech Republic and number three Patrick Rafter of
Australia begins defense of his title against Hicham Arazi of
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Among the women, top seed Martina Hingis of Switzerland will
defend her title but she has to face the most difficult second
round match of any seeded player.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old would face the winner of an opening-round
match between 1997 French Open champion Iva Majoli of Croatia and
Germany's Anke Huber, both former world top 10 players. Majoli
and Huber were seeded fourth and eighth, respectively, at last
year's U.S. Open but have dropped to 20th and 21st in the latest
rankings.
</P>
<P>
Number two Lindsay Davenport of the United States, a
pre-tournament favorite to claim her first Grand Slam singles
title, opens against Catalina Cristea of Romania.
</P>
<P>
Third seed Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic, coming off her
victory at Wimbledon two months ago, meets wildcard Jennifer
Capriati of the United States.
</P>
<P>
No. 4 Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain, the reigning French
Open champion, takes on wildcard Kristina Brandi of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Also, fifth seed Venus Williams of the United States, the
losing finalist to Hingis last year, starts play against Elena
Wagner of Germany.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Monica Seles of the United States, a two-time
winner at the Open, Conchita Martinez of Spain, and Steffi Graf
of Germany, a five-time champion, are all expected to win their
first round matches without difficulties. But Seles stands to
meet Hingis while Graf might face Novotna in the quarterfinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980827.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulls Name Jim Wooldridge Assistant Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- New Chicago Bulls director
of Basketball operations and impending coach Tim Floyd hired his
former teammate Louisiana Tech coach Jim Wooldridge as an
assistant today.
</P>
<P>
Wooldridge announced his resignation from Louisiana Tech this
morning after compiling a 52-59 record over four years at the
school. His team Bulldogs went 12-15 in 1996-97 season, losing in
the first round of the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
Floyd, who has no NBA experience, played together with
Wooldridge in 1975-76 for the Bulldogs. They both graduated from
Louisiana Tech in 1977. Floyd was a student assistant coach the
following year when Wooldridge started 25 of 26 games and
finished third on the team in assists.
</P>
<P>
The 42-year-old Wooldridge began his head coaching career at
Central Missouri, where he compiled a 131-48 mark in six seasons.
He coached at Southwest Texas from 1991-94 before taking over the
Bulldogs in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"Jim is an excellent coach," said Floyd. "He has experience
coaching the triple-post offense and brings values and ideas that
will be important to our staff and organization."
</P>
<P>
Floyd assumed his position with the Bulls on July 23rd and
will likely be named head coach after the lockout. He was
appointed director of basketball operations to leave the window
open for Phil Jackson to return for another season, although
Jackson has said he will not be back.
</P>
<P>
"I'm proud to be able to join the Bulls organization," said
Wooldridge. "It has stood for winning, teaching and class. I'm
looking forward to learning the professional game from the
returning members of the Bull's staff."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
